line = 136 | 1 | true, because up to then he had understood it perfectly; at least, he
line = 137 | 1 | answered my questions exactly as if he did. He and his wife, the old
line = 138 | 1 | lady who had received me, looked at each other in a frightened sort of
line = 139 | 1 | way. He mumbled out that the money had been sent in a letter, and that
line = 140 | 1 | was all he knew. When I asked him if he knew Count Dracula, and could
line = 141 | 1 | tell me anything of his castle, both he and his wife crossed themselves,
line = 142 | 1 | and, saying that they knew nothing at all, simply refused to speak
line = 143 | 1 | further. It was so near the time of starting that I had no time to ask
line = 144 | 1 | any one else, for it was all very mysterious and not by any means
line = 145 | 1 | comforting.
line = 146 | 1 | 
line = 147 | 1 | Just before I was leaving, the old lady came up to my room and said in a
line = 148 | 1 | very hysterical way:
line = 149 | 1 | 
line = 150 | 1 | "Must you go? Oh! young Herr, must you go?" She was in such an excited
line = 151 | 1 | state that she seemed to have lost her grip of what German she knew, and
line = 152 | 1 | mixed it all up with some other language which I did not know at all. I
line = 153 | 1 | was just able to follow her by asking many questions. When I told her
line = 154 | 1 | that I must go at once, and that I was engaged on important business,
line = 155 | 1 | she asked again:
line = 156 | 1 | 
line = 157 | 1 | "Do you know what day it is?" I answered that it was the fourth of May.
line = 158 | 1 | She shook her head as she said again:
line = 159 | 1 | 
line = 160 | 1 | "Oh, yes! I know that! I know that, but do you know what day it is?" On
line = 161 | 1 | my saying that I did not understand, she went on:
line = 162 | 1 | 
line = 163 | 1 | "It is the eve of St. George's Day. Do you not know that to-night, when
line = 164 | 1 | the clock strikes midnight, all the evil things in the world will have
line = 165 | 1 | full sway? Do you know where you are going, and what you are going to?"
line = 166 | 1 | She was in such evident distress that I tried to comfort her, but
line = 167 | 1 | without effect. Finally she went down on her knees and implored me not
line = 168 | 1 | to go; at least to wait a day or two before starting. It was all very
line = 169 | 1 | ridiculous but I did not feel comfortable. However, there was business
line = 170 | 1 | to be done, and I could allow nothing to interfere with it. I therefore
line = 171 | 1 | tried to raise her up, and said, as gravely as I could, that I thanked
line = 172 | 1 | her, but my duty was imperative, and that I must go. She then rose and
line = 173 | 1 | dried her eyes, and taking a crucifix from her neck offered it to me. I
line = 174 | 1 | did not know what to do, for, as an English Churchman, I have been
line = 175 | 1 | taught to regard such things as in some measure idolatrous, and yet it
line = 176 | 1 | seemed so ungracious to refuse an old lady meaning so well and in such a
line = 177 | 1 | state of mind. She saw, I suppose, the doubt in my face, for she put the
line = 178 | 1 | rosary round my neck, and said, "For your mother's sake," and went out
line = 179 | 1 | of the room. I am writing up this part of the diary whilst I am waiting
line = 180 | 1 | for the coach, which is, of course, late; and the crucifix is still
line = 181 | 1 | round my neck. Whether it is the old lady's fear, or the many ghostly
line = 182 | 1 | traditions of this place, or the crucifix itself, I do not know, but I
line = 183 | 1 | am not feeling nearly as easy in my mind as usual. If this book should
line = 184 | 1 | ever reach Mina before I do, let it bring my good-bye. Here comes the
line = 185 | 1 | coach!
line = 186 | 1 | 
line = 187 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 188 | 1 | 
line = 189 | 1 | _5 May. The Castle._--The grey of the morning has passed, and the sun is
line = 190 | 1 | high over the distant horizon, which seems jagged, whether with trees or
line = 191 | 1 | hills I know not, for it is so far off that big things and little are
line = 192 | 1 | mixed. I am not sleepy, and, as I am not to be called till I awake,
line = 193 | 1 | naturally I write till sleep comes. There are many odd things to put
line = 194 | 1 | down, and, lest who reads them may fancy that I dined too well before I
line = 195 | 1 | left Bistritz, let me put down my dinner exactly. I dined on what they
line = 196 | 1 | called "robber steak"--bits of bacon, onion, and beef, seasoned with red
line = 197 | 1 | pepper, and strung on sticks and roasted over the fire, in the simple
line = 198 | 1 | style of the London cat's meat! The wine was Golden Mediasch, which
line = 199 | 1 | produces a queer sting on the tongue, which is, however, not
line = 200 | 1 | disagreeable. I had only a couple of glasses of this, and nothing else.
line = 201 | 1 | 
line = 202 | 1 | When I got on the coach the driver had not taken his seat, and I saw him
line = 203 | 1 | talking with the landlady. They were evidently talking of me, for every
line = 204 | 1 | now and then they looked at me, and some of the people who were sitting
line = 205 | 1 | on the bench outside the door--which they call by a name meaning
line = 206 | 1 | "word-bearer"--came and listened, and then looked at me, most of them
line = 207 | 1 | pityingly. I could hear a lot of words often repeated, queer words, for
line = 208 | 1 | there were many nationalities in the crowd; so I quietly got my polyglot
line = 209 | 1 | dictionary from my bag and looked them out. I must say they were not
line = 210 | 1 | cheering to me, for amongst them were "Ordog"--Satan, "pokol"--hell,
line = 211 | 1 | "stregoica"--witch, "vrolok" and "vlkoslak"--both of which mean the same
line = 212 | 1 | thing, one being Slovak and the other Servian for something that is
line = 213 | 1 | either were-wolf or vampire. (_Mem._, I must ask the Count about these
line = 214 | 1 | superstitions)
line = 215 | 1 | 
line = 216 | 1 | When we started, the crowd round the inn door, which had by this time
line = 217 | 1 | swelled to a considerable size, all made the sign of the cross and
line = 218 | 1 | pointed two fingers towards me. With some difficulty I got a
line = 219 | 1 | fellow-passenger to tell me what they meant; he would not answer at
line = 220 | 1 | first, but on learning that I was English, he explained that it was a
line = 221 | 1 | charm or guard against the evil eye. This was not very pleasant for me,
line = 222 | 1 | just starting for an unknown place to meet an unknown man; but every one
line = 223 | 1 | seemed so kind-hearted, and so sorrowful, and so sympathetic that I
line = 224 | 1 | could not but be touched. I shall never forget the last glimpse which I
line = 225 | 1 | had of the inn-yard and its crowd of picturesque figures, all crossing
line = 226 | 1 | themselves, as they stood round the wide archway, with its background of
line = 227 | 1 | rich foliage of oleander and orange trees in green tubs clustered in the
line = 228 | 1 | centre of the yard. Then our driver, whose wide linen drawers covered
line = 229 | 1 | the whole front of the box-seat--"gotza" they call them--cracked his big
line = 230 | 1 | whip over his four small horses, which ran abreast, and we set off on
line = 231 | 1 | our journey.
line = 232 | 1 | 
line = 233 | 1 | I soon lost sight and recollection of ghostly fears in the beauty of the
line = 234 | 1 | scene as we drove along, although had I known the language, or rather
line = 235 | 1 | languages, which my fellow-passengers were speaking, I might not have
line = 236 | 1 | been able to throw them off so easily. Before us lay a green sloping
line = 237 | 1 | land full of forests and woods, with here and there steep hills, crowned
line = 238 | 1 | with clumps of trees or with farmhouses, the blank gable end to the
line = 239 | 1 | road. There was everywhere a bewildering mass of fruit blossom--apple,
line = 240 | 1 | plum, pear, cherry; and as we drove by I could see the green grass under
line = 241 | 1 | the trees spangled with the fallen petals. In and out amongst these
line = 242 | 1 | green hills of what they call here the "Mittel Land" ran the road,
line = 243 | 1 | losing itself as it swept round the grassy curve, or was shut out by the
line = 244 | 1 | straggling ends of pine woods, which here and there ran down the
line = 245 | 1 | hillsides like tongues of flame. The road was rugged, but still we
line = 246 | 1 | seemed to fly over it with a feverish haste. I could not understand then
line = 247 | 1 | what the haste meant, but the driver was evidently bent on losing no
line = 248 | 1 | time in reaching Borgo Prund. I was told that this road is in summertime
line = 249 | 1 | excellent, but that it had not yet been put in order after the winter
line = 250 | 1 | snows. In this respect it is different from the general run of roads in
line = 251 | 1 | the Carpathians, for it is an old tradition that they are not to be kept
line = 252 | 1 | in too good order. Of old the Hospadars would not repair them, lest the
line = 253 | 1 | Turk should think that they were preparing to bring in foreign troops,
line = 254 | 1 | and so hasten the war which was always really at loading point.
line = 255 | 1 | 
line = 256 | 1 | Beyond the green swelling hills of the Mittel Land rose mighty slopes
line = 257 | 1 | of forest up to the lofty steeps of the Carpathians themselves. Right
line = 258 | 1 | and left of us they towered, with the afternoon sun falling full upon
line = 259 | 1 | them and bringing out all the glorious colours of this beautiful range,
line = 260 | 1 | deep blue and purple in the shadows of the peaks, green and brown where
line = 261 | 1 | grass and rock mingled, and an endless perspective of jagged rock and
line = 262 | 1 | pointed crags, till these were themselves lost in the distance, where
line = 263 | 1 | the snowy peaks rose grandly. Here and there seemed mighty rifts in the
line = 264 | 1 | mountains, through which, as the sun began to sink, we saw now and again
line = 265 | 1 | the white gleam of falling water. One of my companions touched my arm as
line = 266 | 1 | we swept round the base of a hill and opened up the lofty, snow-covered
line = 267 | 1 | peak of a mountain, which seemed, as we wound on our serpentine way, to
line = 268 | 1 | be right before us:--
line = 269 | 1 | 
line = 270 | 1 | "Look! Isten szek!"--"God's seat!"--and he crossed himself reverently.
line = 271 | 1 | 
line = 272 | 1 | As we wound on our endless way, and the sun sank lower and lower behind
line = 273 | 1 | us, the shadows of the evening began to creep round us. This was
line = 274 | 1 | emphasised by the fact that the snowy mountain-top still held the
line = 275 | 1 | sunset, and seemed to glow out with a delicate cool pink. Here and there
line = 276 | 1 | we passed Cszeks and Slovaks, all in picturesque attire, but I noticed
line = 277 | 1 | that goitre was painfully prevalent. By the roadside were many crosses,
line = 278 | 1 | and as we swept by, my companions all crossed themselves. Here and there
line = 279 | 1 | was a peasant man or woman kneeling before a shrine, who did not even
line = 280 | 1 | turn round as we approached, but seemed in the self-surrender of
line = 281 | 1 | devotion to have neither eyes nor ears for the outer world. There were
line = 282 | 1 | many things new to me: for instance, hay-ricks in the trees, and here
line = 283 | 1 | and there very beautiful masses of weeping birch, their white stems
line = 284 | 1 | shining like silver through the delicate green of the leaves. Now and
line = 285 | 1 | again we passed a leiter-wagon--the ordinary peasant's cart--with its
line = 286 | 1 | long, snake-like vertebra, calculated to suit the inequalities of the
line = 287 | 1 | road. On this were sure to be seated quite a group of home-coming
line = 288 | 1 | peasants, the Cszeks with their white, and the Slovaks with their
line = 289 | 1 | coloured, sheepskins, the latter carrying lance-fashion their long
line = 290 | 1 | staves, with axe at end. As the evening fell it began to get very cold,
line = 291 | 1 | and the growing twilight seemed to merge into one dark mistiness the
line = 292 | 1 | gloom of the trees, oak, beech, and pine, though in the valleys which
line = 293 | 1 | ran deep between the spurs of the hills, as we ascended through the
line = 294 | 1 | Pass, the dark firs stood out here and there against the background of
line = 295 | 1 | late-lying snow. Sometimes, as the road was cut through the pine woods
line = 296 | 1 | that seemed in the darkness to be closing down upon us, great masses of
line = 297 | 1 | greyness, which here and there bestrewed the trees, produced a
line = 298 | 1 | peculiarly weird and solemn effect, which carried on the thoughts and
line = 299 | 1 | grim fancies engendered earlier in the evening, when the falling sunset
line = 300 | 1 | threw into strange relief the ghost-like clouds which amongst the
line = 301 | 1 | Carpathians seem to wind ceaselessly through the valleys. Sometimes the
line = 302 | 1 | hills were so steep that, despite our driver's haste, the horses could
line = 303 | 1 | only go slowly. I wished to get down and walk up them, as we do at home,
line = 304 | 1 | but the driver would not hear of it. "No, no," he said; "you must not
line = 305 | 1 | walk here; the dogs are too fierce"; and then he added, with what he
line = 306 | 1 | evidently meant for grim pleasantry--for he looked round to catch the
line = 307 | 1 | approving smile of the rest--"and you may have enough of such matters
line = 308 | 1 | before you go to sleep." The only stop he would make was a moment's
line = 309 | 1 | pause to light his lamps.
line = 310 | 1 | 
line = 311 | 1 | When it grew dark there seemed to be some excitement amongst the
line = 312 | 1 | passengers, and they kept speaking to him, one after the other, as
line = 313 | 1 | though urging him to further speed. He lashed the horses unmercifully
line = 314 | 1 | with his long whip, and with wild cries of encouragement urged them on
line = 315 | 1 | to further exertions. Then through the darkness I could see a sort of
line = 316 | 1 | patch of grey light ahead of us, as though there were a cleft in the
line = 317 | 1 | hills. The excitement of the passengers grew greater; the crazy coach
line = 318 | 1 | rocked on its great leather springs, and swayed like a boat tossed on a
line = 319 | 1 | stormy sea. I had to hold on. The road grew more level, and we appeared
line = 320 | 1 | to fly along. Then the mountains seemed to come nearer to us on each
line = 321 | 1 | side and to frown down upon us; we were entering on the Borgo Pass. One
line = 322 | 1 | by one several of the passengers offered me gifts, which they pressed
line = 323 | 1 | upon me with an earnestness which would take no denial; these were
line = 324 | 1 | certainly of an odd and varied kind, but each was given in simple good
line = 325 | 1 | faith, with a kindly word, and a blessing, and that strange mixture of
line = 326 | 1 | fear-meaning movements which I had seen outside the hotel at
line = 327 | 1 | Bistritz--the sign of the cross and the guard against the evil eye.
line = 328 | 1 | Then, as we flew along, the driver leaned forward, and on each side the
line = 329 | 1 | passengers, craning over the edge of the coach, peered eagerly into the
line = 330 | 1 | darkness. It was evident that something very exciting was either
line = 331 | 1 | happening or expected, but though I asked each passenger, no one would
line = 332 | 1 | give me the slightest explanation. This state of excitement kept on for
line = 333 | 1 | some little time; and at last we saw before us the Pass opening out on
line = 334 | 1 | the eastern side. There were dark, rolling clouds overhead, and in the
line = 335 | 1 | air the heavy, oppressive sense of thunder. It seemed as though the
line = 336 | 1 | mountain range had separated two atmospheres, and that now we had got
line = 337 | 1 | into the thunderous one. I was now myself looking out for the conveyance
line = 338 | 1 | which was to take me to the Count. Each moment I expected to see the
line = 339 | 1 | glare of lamps through the blackness; but all was dark. The only light
line = 340 | 1 | was the flickering rays of our own lamps, in which the steam from our
line = 341 | 1 | hard-driven horses rose in a white cloud. We could see now the sandy
line = 342 | 1 | road lying white before us, but there was on it no sign of a vehicle.
line = 343 | 1 | The passengers drew back with a sigh of gladness, which seemed to mock
line = 344 | 1 | my own disappointment. I was already thinking what I had best do, when
line = 345 | 1 | the driver, looking at his watch, said to the others something which I
line = 346 | 1 | could hardly hear, it was spoken so quietly and in so low a tone; I
line = 347 | 1 | thought it was "An hour less than the time." Then turning to me, he said
line = 348 | 1 | in German worse than my own:--
line = 349 | 1 | 
line = 350 | 1 | "There is no carriage here. The Herr is not expected after all. He will
line = 351 | 1 | now come on to Bukovina, and return to-morrow or the next day; better
line = 352 | 1 | the next day." Whilst he was speaking the horses began to neigh and
line = 353 | 1 | snort and plunge wildly, so that the driver had to hold them up. Then,
line = 354 | 1 | amongst a chorus of screams from the peasants and a universal crossing
line = 355 | 1 | of themselves, a calèche, with four horses, drove up behind us, overtook
line = 356 | 1 | us, and drew up beside the coach. I could see from the flash of our
line = 357 | 1 | lamps, as the rays fell on them, that the horses were coal-black and
line = 358 | 1 | splendid animals. They were driven by a tall man, with a long brown
line = 359 | 1 | beard and a great black hat, which seemed to hide his face from us. I
line = 360 | 1 | could only see the gleam of a pair of very bright eyes, which seemed red
line = 361 | 1 | in the lamplight, as he turned to us. He said to the driver:--
line = 362 | 1 | 
line = 363 | 1 | "You are early to-night, my friend." The man stammered in reply:--
line = 364 | 1 | 
line = 365 | 1 | "The English Herr was in a hurry," to which the stranger replied:--
line = 366 | 1 | 
line = 367 | 1 | "That is why, I suppose, you wished him to go on to Bukovina. You cannot
line = 368 | 1 | deceive me, my friend; I know too much, and my horses are swift." As he
line = 369 | 1 | spoke he smiled, and the lamplight fell on a hard-looking mouth, with
line = 370 | 1 | very red lips and sharp-looking teeth, as white as ivory. One of my
line = 371 | 1 | companions whispered to another the line from Burger's "Lenore":--
line = 372 | 1 | 
line = 373 | 1 |     "Denn die Todten reiten schnell"--
line = 374 | 1 |     ("For the dead travel fast.")
line = 375 | 1 | 
line = 376 | 1 | The strange driver evidently heard the words, for he looked up with a
line = 377 | 1 | gleaming smile. The passenger turned his face away, at the same time
line = 378 | 1 | putting out his two fingers and crossing himself. "Give me the Herr's
line = 379 | 1 | luggage," said the driver; and with exceeding alacrity my bags were
line = 380 | 1 | handed out and put in the calèche. Then I descended from the side of the
line = 381 | 1 | coach, as the calèche was close alongside, the driver helping me with a
line = 382 | 1 | hand which caught my arm in a grip of steel; his strength must have been
line = 383 | 1 | prodigious. Without a word he shook his reins, the horses turned, and we
line = 384 | 1 | swept into the darkness of the Pass. As I looked back I saw the steam
line = 385 | 1 | from the horses of the coach by the light of the lamps, and projected
line = 386 | 1 | against it the figures of my late companions crossing themselves. Then
line = 387 | 1 | the driver cracked his whip and called to his horses, and off they swept
line = 388 | 1 | on their way to Bukovina. As they sank into the darkness I felt a
line = 389 | 1 | strange chill, and a lonely feeling came over me; but a cloak was thrown
line = 390 | 1 | over my shoulders, and a rug across my knees, and the driver said in
line = 391 | 1 | excellent German:--
line = 392 | 1 | 
line = 393 | 1 | "The night is chill, mein Herr, and my master the Count bade me take all
line = 394 | 1 | care of you. There is a flask of slivovitz (the plum brandy of the
line = 395 | 1 | country) underneath the seat, if you should require it." I did not take
line = 396 | 1 | any, but it was a comfort to know it was there all the same. I felt a
line = 397 | 1 | little strangely, and not a little frightened. I think had there been
line = 398 | 1 | any alternative I should have taken it, instead of prosecuting that
line = 399 | 1 | unknown night journey. The carriage went at a hard pace straight along,
line = 400 | 1 | then we made a complete turn and went along another straight road. It
line = 401 | 1 | seemed to me that we were simply going over and over the same ground
line = 402 | 1 | again; and so I took note of some salient point, and found that this was
line = 403 | 1 | so. I would have liked to have asked the driver what this all meant, but
line = 404 | 1 | I really feared to do so, for I thought that, placed as I was, any
line = 405 | 1 | protest would have had no effect in case there had been an intention to
line = 406 | 1 | delay. By-and-by, however, as I was curious to know how time was
line = 407 | 1 | passing, I struck a match, and by its flame looked at my watch; it was
line = 408 | 1 | within a few minutes of midnight. This gave me a sort of shock, for I
line = 409 | 1 | suppose the general superstition about midnight was increased by my
line = 410 | 1 | recent experiences. I waited with a sick feeling of suspense.
line = 411 | 1 | 
line = 412 | 1 | Then a dog began to howl somewhere in a farmhouse far down the road--a
line = 413 | 1 | long, agonised wailing, as if from fear. The sound was taken up by
line = 414 | 1 | another dog, and then another and another, till, borne on the wind which
line = 415 | 1 | now sighed softly through the Pass, a wild howling began, which seemed
line = 416 | 1 | to come from all over the country, as far as the imagination could grasp
line = 417 | 1 | it through the gloom of the night. At the first howl the horses began to
line = 418 | 1 | strain and rear, but the driver spoke to them soothingly, and they
line = 419 | 1 | quieted down, but shivered and sweated as though after a runaway from
line = 420 | 1 | sudden fright. Then, far off in the distance, from the mountains on each
line = 421 | 1 | side of us began a louder and a sharper howling--that of wolves--which
line = 422 | 1 | affected both the horses and myself in the same way--for I was minded to
line = 423 | 1 | jump from the calèche and run, whilst they reared again and plunged
line = 424 | 1 | madly, so that the driver had to use all his great strength to keep them
line = 425 | 1 | from bolting. In a few minutes, however, my own ears got accustomed to
line = 426 | 1 | the sound, and the horses so far became quiet that the driver was able
line = 427 | 1 | to descend and to stand before them. He petted and soothed them, and
line = 428 | 1 | whispered something in their ears, as I have heard of horse-tamers
line = 429 | 1 | doing, and with extraordinary effect, for under his caresses they became
line = 430 | 1 | quite manageable again, though they still trembled. The driver again
line = 431 | 1 | took his seat, and shaking his reins, started off at a great pace. This
line = 432 | 1 | time, after going to the far side of the Pass, he suddenly turned down a
line = 433 | 1 | narrow roadway which ran sharply to the right.
line = 434 | 1 | 
line = 435 | 1 | Soon we were hemmed in with trees, which in places arched right over the
line = 436 | 1 | roadway till we passed as through a tunnel; and again great frowning
line = 437 | 1 | rocks guarded us boldly on either side. Though we were in shelter, we
line = 438 | 1 | could hear the rising wind, for it moaned and whistled through the
line = 439 | 1 | rocks, and the branches of the trees crashed together as we swept along.
line = 440 | 1 | It grew colder and colder still, and fine, powdery snow began to fall,
line = 441 | 1 | so that soon we and all around us were covered with a white blanket. The
line = 442 | 1 | keen wind still carried the howling of the dogs, though this grew
line = 443 | 1 | fainter as we went on our way. The baying of the wolves sounded nearer
line = 444 | 1 | and nearer, as though they were closing round on us from every side. I
line = 445 | 1 | grew dreadfully afraid, and the horses shared my fear. The driver,
line = 446 | 1 | however, was not in the least disturbed; he kept turning his head to
line = 447 | 1 | left and right, but I could not see anything through the darkness.
line = 448 | 1 | 
line = 449 | 1 | Suddenly, away on our left, I saw a faint flickering blue flame. The
line = 450 | 1 | driver saw it at the same moment; he at once checked the horses, and,
line = 451 | 1 | jumping to the ground, disappeared into the darkness. I did not know
line = 452 | 1 | what to do, the less as the howling of the wolves grew closer; but while
line = 453 | 1 | I wondered the driver suddenly appeared again, and without a word took
line = 454 | 1 | his seat, and we resumed our journey. I think I must have fallen asleep
line = 455 | 1 | and kept dreaming of the incident, for it seemed to be repeated
line = 456 | 1 | endlessly, and now looking back, it is like a sort of awful nightmare.
line = 457 | 1 | Once the flame appeared so near the road, that even in the darkness
line = 458 | 1 | around us I could watch the driver's motions. He went rapidly to where
line = 459 | 1 | the blue flame arose--it must have been very faint, for it did not seem
line = 460 | 1 | to illumine the place around it at all--and gathering a few stones,
line = 461 | 1 | formed them into some device. Once there appeared a strange optical
line = 462 | 1 | effect: when he stood between me and the flame he did not obstruct it,
line = 463 | 1 | for I could see its ghostly flicker all the same. This startled me, but
line = 464 | 1 | as the effect was only momentary, I took it that my eyes deceived me
line = 465 | 1 | straining through the darkness. Then for a time there were no blue
line = 466 | 1 | flames, and we sped onwards through the gloom, with the howling of the
line = 467 | 1 | wolves around us, as though they were following in a moving circle.
line = 468 | 1 | 
line = 469 | 1 | At last there came a time when the driver went further afield than he
line = 470 | 1 | had yet gone, and during his absence, the horses began to tremble worse
line = 471 | 1 | than ever and to snort and scream with fright. I could not see any cause
line = 472 | 1 | for it, for the howling of the wolves had ceased altogether; but just
line = 473 | 1 | then the moon, sailing through the black clouds, appeared behind the
line = 474 | 1 | jagged crest of a beetling, pine-clad rock, and by its light I saw
line = 475 | 1 | around us a ring of wolves, with white teeth and lolling red tongues,
line = 476 | 1 | with long, sinewy limbs and shaggy hair. They were a hundred times more
line = 477 | 1 | terrible in the grim silence which held them than even when they howled.
line = 478 | 1 | For myself, I felt a sort of paralysis of fear. It is only when a man
line = 479 | 1 | feels himself face to face with such horrors that he can understand
line = 480 | 1 | their true import.
line = 481 | 1 | 
line = 482 | 1 | All at once the wolves began to howl as though the moonlight had had
line = 483 | 1 | some peculiar effect on them. The horses jumped about and reared, and
line = 484 | 1 | looked helplessly round with eyes that rolled in a way painful to see;
line = 485 | 1 | but the living ring of terror encompassed them on every side; and they
line = 486 | 1 | had perforce to remain within it. I called to the coachman to come, for
line = 487 | 1 | it seemed to me that our only chance was to try to break out through the
line = 488 | 1 | ring and to aid his approach. I shouted and beat the side of the
line = 489 | 1 | calèche, hoping by the noise to scare the wolves from that side, so as
line = 490 | 1 | to give him a chance of reaching the trap. How he came there, I know
line = 491 | 1 | not, but I heard his voice raised in a tone of imperious command, and
line = 492 | 1 | looking towards the sound, saw him stand in the roadway. As he swept his
line = 493 | 1 | long arms, as though brushing aside some impalpable obstacle, the wolves
line = 494 | 1 | fell back and back further still. Just then a heavy cloud passed across
line = 495 | 1 | the face of the moon, so that we were again in darkness.
line = 496 | 1 | 
line = 497 | 1 | When I could see again the driver was climbing into the calèche, and the
line = 498 | 1 | wolves had disappeared. This was all so strange and uncanny that a
line = 499 | 1 | dreadful fear came upon me, and I was afraid to speak or move. The time
line = 500 | 1 | seemed interminable as we swept on our way, now in almost complete
line = 501 | 1 | darkness, for the rolling clouds obscured the moon. We kept on
line = 502 | 1 | ascending, with occasional periods of quick descent, but in the main
line = 503 | 1 | always ascending. Suddenly, I became conscious of the fact that the
line = 504 | 1 | driver was in the act of pulling up the horses in the courtyard of a
line = 505 | 1 | vast ruined castle, from whose tall black windows came no ray of light,
line = 506 | 1 | and whose broken battlements showed a jagged line against the moonlit
line = 507 | 1 | sky.
line = 508 | 1 | 
line = 509 | 1 | 
line = 510 | 1 | 
line = 511 | 1 | 
line = 512 | 1 | CHAPTER II
line = 513 | 1 | 
line = 514 | 1 | JONATHAN HARKER'S JOURNAL--_continued_
line = 515 | 1 | 
line = 516 | 1 | 
line = 517 | 1 | _5 May._--I must have been asleep, for certainly if I had been fully
line = 518 | 1 | awake I must have noticed the approach of such a remarkable place. In
line = 519 | 1 | the gloom the courtyard looked of considerable size, and as several dark
line = 520 | 1 | ways led from it under great round arches, it perhaps seemed bigger than
line = 521 | 1 | it really is. I have not yet been able to see it by daylight.
line = 522 | 1 | 
line = 523 | 1 | When the calèche stopped, the driver jumped down and held out his hand
line = 524 | 1 | to assist me to alight. Again I could not but notice his prodigious
line = 525 | 1 | strength. His hand actually seemed like a steel vice that could have
line = 526 | 1 | crushed mine if he had chosen. Then he took out my traps, and placed
line = 527 | 1 | them on the ground beside me as I stood close to a great door, old and
line = 528 | 1 | studded with large iron nails, and set in a projecting doorway of
line = 529 | 1 | massive stone. I could see even in the dim light that the stone was
line = 530 | 1 | massively carved, but that the carving had been much worn by time and
line = 531 | 1 | weather. As I stood, the driver jumped again into his seat and shook the
line = 532 | 1 | reins; the horses started forward, and trap and all disappeared down one
line = 533 | 1 | of the dark openings.
line = 534 | 1 | 
line = 535 | 1 | I stood in silence where I was, for I did not know what to do. Of bell
line = 536 | 1 | or knocker there was no sign; through these frowning walls and dark
line = 537 | 1 | window openings it was not likely that my voice could penetrate. The
line = 538 | 1 | time I waited seemed endless, and I felt doubts and fears crowding upon
line = 539 | 1 | me. What sort of place had I come to, and among what kind of people?
line = 540 | 1 | What sort of grim adventure was it on which I had embarked? Was this a
line = 541 | 1 | customary incident in the life of a solicitor's clerk sent out to
line = 542 | 1 | explain the purchase of a London estate to a foreigner? Solicitor's
line = 543 | 1 | clerk! Mina would not like that. Solicitor--for just before leaving
line = 544 | 1 | London I got word that my examination was successful; and I am now a
line = 545 | 1 | full-blown solicitor! I began to rub my eyes and pinch myself to see if
line = 546 | 1 | I were awake. It all seemed like a horrible nightmare to me, and I
line = 547 | 1 | expected that I should suddenly awake, and find myself at home, with
line = 548 | 1 | the dawn struggling in through the windows, as I had now and again felt
line = 549 | 1 | in the morning after a day of overwork. But my flesh answered the
line = 550 | 1 | pinching test, and my eyes were not to be deceived. I was indeed awake
line = 551 | 1 | and among the Carpathians. All I could do now was to be patient, and to
line = 552 | 1 | wait the coming of the morning.
line = 553 | 1 | 
line = 554 | 1 | Just as I had come to this conclusion I heard a heavy step approaching
line = 555 | 1 | behind the great door, and saw through the chinks the gleam of a coming
line = 556 | 1 | light. Then there was the sound of rattling chains and the clanking of
line = 557 | 1 | massive bolts drawn back. A key was turned with the loud grating noise
line = 558 | 1 | of long disuse, and the great door swung back.
line = 559 | 1 | 
line = 560 | 1 | Within, stood a tall old man, clean shaven save for a long white
line = 561 | 1 | moustache, and clad in black from head to foot, without a single speck
line = 562 | 1 | of colour about him anywhere. He held in his hand an antique silver
line = 563 | 1 | lamp, in which the flame burned without chimney or globe of any kind,
line = 564 | 1 | throwing long quivering shadows as it flickered in the draught of the
line = 565 | 1 | open door. The old man motioned me in with his right hand with a courtly
line = 566 | 1 | gesture, saying in excellent English, but with a strange intonation:--
line = 567 | 1 | 
line = 568 | 1 | "Welcome to my house! Enter freely and of your own will!" He made no
line = 569 | 1 | motion of stepping to meet me, but stood like a statue, as though his
line = 570 | 1 | gesture of welcome had fixed him into stone. The instant, however, that
line = 571 | 1 | I had stepped over the threshold, he moved impulsively forward, and
line = 572 | 1 | holding out his hand grasped mine with a strength which made me wince,
line = 573 | 1 | an effect which was not lessened by the fact that it seemed as cold as
line = 574 | 1 | ice--more like the hand of a dead than a living man. Again he said:--
line = 575 | 1 | 
line = 576 | 1 | "Welcome to my house. Come freely. Go safely; and leave something of the
line = 577 | 1 | happiness you bring!" The strength of the handshake was so much akin to
line = 578 | 1 | that which I had noticed in the driver, whose face I had not seen, that
line = 579 | 1 | for a moment I doubted if it were not the same person to whom I was
line = 580 | 1 | speaking; so to make sure, I said interrogatively:--
line = 581 | 1 | 
line = 582 | 1 | "Count Dracula?" He bowed in a courtly way as he replied:--
line = 583 | 1 | 
line = 584 | 1 | "I am Dracula; and I bid you welcome, Mr. Harker, to my house. Come in;
line = 585 | 1 | the night air is chill, and you must need to eat and rest." As he was
line = 586 | 1 | speaking, he put the lamp on a bracket on the wall, and stepping out,
line = 587 | 1 | took my luggage; he had carried it in before I could forestall him. I
line = 588 | 1 | protested but he insisted:--
line = 589 | 1 | 
line = 590 | 1 | "Nay, sir, you are my guest. It is late, and my people are not
line = 591 | 1 | available. Let me see to your comfort myself." He insisted on carrying
line = 592 | 1 | my traps along the passage, and then up a great winding stair, and
line = 593 | 1 | along another great passage, on whose stone floor our steps rang
line = 594 | 1 | heavily. At the end of this he threw open a heavy door, and I rejoiced
line = 595 | 1 | to see within a well-lit room in which a table was spread for supper,
line = 596 | 1 | and on whose mighty hearth a great fire of logs, freshly replenished,
line = 597 | 1 | flamed and flared.
line = 598 | 1 | 
line = 599 | 1 | The Count halted, putting down my bags, closed the door, and crossing
line = 600 | 1 | the room, opened another door, which led into a small octagonal room lit
line = 601 | 1 | by a single lamp, and seemingly without a window of any sort. Passing
line = 602 | 1 | through this, he opened another door, and motioned me to enter. It was a
line = 603 | 1 | welcome sight; for here was a great bedroom well lighted and warmed with
line = 604 | 1 | another log fire,--also added to but lately, for the top logs were
line = 605 | 1 | fresh--which sent a hollow roar up the wide chimney. The Count himself
line = 606 | 1 | left my luggage inside and withdrew, saying, before he closed the
line = 607 | 1 | door:--
line = 608 | 1 | 
line = 609 | 1 | "You will need, after your journey, to refresh yourself by making your
line = 610 | 1 | toilet. I trust you will find all you wish. When you are ready, come
line = 611 | 1 | into the other room, where you will find your supper prepared."
line = 612 | 1 | 
line = 613 | 1 | The light and warmth and the Count's courteous welcome seemed to have
line = 614 | 1 | dissipated all my doubts and fears. Having then reached my normal state,
line = 615 | 1 | I discovered that I was half famished with hunger; so making a hasty
line = 616 | 1 | toilet, I went into the other room.
line = 617 | 1 | 
line = 618 | 1 | I found supper already laid out. My host, who stood on one side of the
line = 619 | 1 | great fireplace, leaning against the stonework, made a graceful wave of
line = 620 | 1 | his hand to the table, and said:--
line = 621 | 1 | 
line = 622 | 1 | "I pray you, be seated and sup how you please. You will, I trust, excuse
line = 623 | 1 | me that I do not join you; but I have dined already, and I do not sup."
line = 624 | 1 | 
line = 625 | 1 | I handed to him the sealed letter which Mr. Hawkins had entrusted to me.
line = 626 | 1 | He opened it and read it gravely; then, with a charming smile, he handed
line = 627 | 1 | it to me to read. One passage of it, at least, gave me a thrill of
line = 628 | 1 | pleasure.
line = 629 | 1 | 
line = 630 | 1 | "I must regret that an attack of gout, from which malady I am a constant
line = 631 | 1 | sufferer, forbids absolutely any travelling on my part for some time to
line = 632 | 1 | come; but I am happy to say I can send a sufficient substitute, one in
line = 633 | 1 | whom I have every possible confidence. He is a young man, full of energy
line = 634 | 1 | and talent in his own way, and of a very faithful disposition. He is
line = 635 | 1 | discreet and silent, and has grown into manhood in my service. He shall
line = 636 | 1 | be ready to attend on you when you will during his stay, and shall take
line = 637 | 1 | your instructions in all matters."
line = 638 | 1 | 
line = 639 | 1 | The Count himself came forward and took off the cover of a dish, and I
line = 640 | 1 | fell to at once on an excellent roast chicken. This, with some cheese
line = 641 | 1 | and a salad and a bottle of old Tokay, of which I had two glasses, was
line = 642 | 1 | my supper. During the time I was eating it the Count asked me many
line = 643 | 1 | questions as to my journey, and I told him by degrees all I had
line = 644 | 1 | experienced.
line = 645 | 1 | 
line = 646 | 1 | By this time I had finished my supper, and by my host's desire had drawn
line = 647 | 1 | up a chair by the fire and begun to smoke a cigar which he offered me,
line = 648 | 1 | at the same time excusing himself that he did not smoke. I had now an
line = 649 | 1 | opportunity of observing him, and found him of a very marked
line = 650 | 1 | physiognomy.
line = 651 | 1 | 
line = 652 | 1 | His face was a strong--a very strong--aquiline, with high bridge of the
line = 653 | 1 | thin nose and peculiarly arched nostrils; with lofty domed forehead, and
line = 654 | 1 | hair growing scantily round the temples but profusely elsewhere. His
line = 655 | 1 | eyebrows were very massive, almost meeting over the nose, and with bushy
line = 656 | 1 | hair that seemed to curl in its own profusion. The mouth, so far as I
line = 657 | 1 | could see it under the heavy moustache, was fixed and rather
line = 658 | 1 | cruel-looking, with peculiarly sharp white teeth; these protruded over
line = 659 | 1 | the lips, whose remarkable ruddiness showed astonishing vitality in a
line = 660 | 1 | man of his years. For the rest, his ears were pale, and at the tops
line = 661 | 1 | extremely pointed; the chin was broad and strong, and the cheeks firm
line = 662 | 1 | though thin. The general effect was one of extraordinary pallor.
line = 663 | 1 | 
line = 664 | 1 | Hitherto I had noticed the backs of his hands as they lay on his knees
line = 665 | 1 | in the firelight, and they had seemed rather white and fine; but seeing
line = 666 | 1 | them now close to me, I could not but notice that they were rather
line = 667 | 1 | coarse--broad, with squat fingers. Strange to say, there were hairs in
line = 668 | 1 | the centre of the palm. The nails were long and fine, and cut to a sharp
line = 669 | 1 | point. As the Count leaned over me and his hands touched me, I could not
line = 670 | 1 | repress a shudder. It may have been that his breath was rank, but a
line = 671 | 1 | horrible feeling of nausea came over me, which, do what I would, I could
line = 672 | 1 | not conceal. The Count, evidently noticing it, drew back; and with a
line = 673 | 1 | grim sort of smile, which showed more than he had yet done his
line = 674 | 1 | protuberant teeth, sat himself down again on his own side of the
line = 675 | 1 | fireplace. We were both silent for a while; and as I looked towards the
line = 676 | 1 | window I saw the first dim streak of the coming dawn. There seemed a
line = 677 | 1 | strange stillness over everything; but as I listened I heard as if from
line = 678 | 1 | down below in the valley the howling of many wolves. The Count's eyes
line = 679 | 1 | gleamed, and he said:--
line = 680 | 1 | 
line = 681 | 1 | "Listen to them--the children of the night. What music they make!"
line = 682 | 1 | Seeing, I suppose, some expression in my face strange to him, he
line = 683 | 1 | added:--
line = 684 | 1 | 
line = 685 | 1 | "Ah, sir, you dwellers in the city cannot enter into the feelings of the
line = 686 | 1 | hunter." Then he rose and said:--
line = 687 | 1 | 
line = 688 | 1 | "But you must be tired. Your bedroom is all ready, and to-morrow you
line = 689 | 1 | shall sleep as late as you will. I have to be away till the afternoon;
line = 690 | 1 | so sleep well and dream well!" With a courteous bow, he opened for me
line = 691 | 1 | himself the door to the octagonal room, and I entered my bedroom....
line = 692 | 1 | 
line = 693 | 1 | I am all in a sea of wonders. I doubt; I fear; I think strange things,
line = 694 | 1 | which I dare not confess to my own soul. God keep me, if only for the
line = 695 | 1 | sake of those dear to me!
line = 696 | 1 | 
line = 697 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 698 | 1 | 
line = 699 | 1 | _7 May._--It is again early morning, but I have rested and enjoyed the
line = 700 | 1 | last twenty-four hours. I slept till late in the day, and awoke of my
line = 701 | 1 | own accord. When I had dressed myself I went into the room where we had
line = 702 | 1 | supped, and found a cold breakfast laid out, with coffee kept hot by the
line = 703 | 1 | pot being placed on the hearth. There was a card on the table, on which
line = 704 | 1 | was written:--
line = 705 | 1 | 
line = 706 | 1 | "I have to be absent for a while. Do not wait for me.--D." I set to and
line = 707 | 1 | enjoyed a hearty meal. When I had done, I looked for a bell, so that I
line = 708 | 1 | might let the servants know I had finished; but I could not find one.
line = 709 | 1 | There are certainly odd deficiencies in the house, considering the
line = 710 | 1 | extraordinary evidences of wealth which are round me. The table service
line = 711 | 1 | is of gold, and so beautifully wrought that it must be of immense value.
line = 712 | 1 | The curtains and upholstery of the chairs and sofas and the hangings of
line = 713 | 1 | my bed are of the costliest and most beautiful fabrics, and must have
line = 714 | 1 | been of fabulous value when they were made, for they are centuries old,
line = 715 | 1 | though in excellent order. I saw something like them in Hampton Court,
line = 716 | 1 | but there they were worn and frayed and moth-eaten. But still in none of
line = 717 | 1 | the rooms is there a mirror. There is not even a toilet glass on my
line = 718 | 1 | table, and I had to get the little shaving glass from my bag before I
line = 719 | 1 | could either shave or brush my hair. I have not yet seen a servant
line = 720 | 1 | anywhere, or heard a sound near the castle except the howling of wolves.
line = 721 | 1 | Some time after I had finished my meal--I do not know whether to call it
line = 722 | 1 | breakfast or dinner, for it was between five and six o'clock when I had
line = 723 | 1 | it--I looked about for something to read, for I did not like to go about
line = 724 | 1 | the castle until I had asked the Count's permission. There was
line = 725 | 1 | absolutely nothing in the room, book, newspaper, or even writing
line = 726 | 1 | materials; so I opened another door in the room and found a sort of
line = 727 | 1 | library. The door opposite mine I tried, but found it locked.
line = 728 | 1 | 
line = 729 | 1 | In the library I found, to my great delight, a vast number of English
line = 730 | 1 | books, whole shelves full of them, and bound volumes of magazines and
line = 731 | 1 | newspapers. A table in the centre was littered with English magazines
line = 732 | 1 | and newspapers, though none of them were of very recent date. The books
line = 733 | 1 | were of the most varied kind--history, geography, politics, political
line = 734 | 1 | economy, botany, geology, law--all relating to England and English life
line = 735 | 1 | and customs and manners. There were even such books of reference as the
line = 736 | 1 | London Directory, the "Red" and "Blue" books, Whitaker's Almanac, the
line = 737 | 1 | Army and Navy Lists, and--it somehow gladdened my heart to see it--the
line = 738 | 1 | Law List.
line = 739 | 1 | 
line = 740 | 1 | Whilst I was looking at the books, the door opened, and the Count
line = 741 | 1 | entered. He saluted me in a hearty way, and hoped that I had had a good
line = 742 | 1 | night's rest. Then he went on:--
line = 743 | 1 | 
line = 744 | 1 | "I am glad you found your way in here, for I am sure there is much that
line = 745 | 1 | will interest you. These companions"--and he laid his hand on some of
line = 746 | 1 | the books--"have been good friends to me, and for some years past, ever
line = 747 | 1 | since I had the idea of going to London, have given me many, many hours
line = 748 | 1 | of pleasure. Through them I have come to know your great England; and to
line = 749 | 1 | know her is to love her. I long to go through the crowded streets of
line = 750 | 1 | your mighty London, to be in the midst of the whirl and rush of
line = 751 | 1 | humanity, to share its life, its change, its death, and all that makes
line = 752 | 1 | it what it is. But alas! as yet I only know your tongue through books.
line = 753 | 1 | To you, my friend, I look that I know it to speak."
line = 754 | 1 | 
line = 755 | 1 | "But, Count," I said, "you know and speak English thoroughly!" He bowed
line = 756 | 1 | gravely.
line = 757 | 1 | 
line = 758 | 1 | "I thank you, my friend, for your all too-flattering estimate, but yet I
line = 759 | 1 | fear that I am but a little way on the road I would travel. True, I know
line = 760 | 1 | the grammar and the words, but yet I know not how to speak them."
line = 761 | 1 | 
line = 762 | 1 | "Indeed," I said, "you speak excellently."
line = 763 | 1 | 
line = 764 | 1 | "Not so," he answered. "Well, I know that, did I move and speak in your
line = 765 | 1 | London, none there are who would not know me for a stranger. That is not
line = 766 | 1 | enough for me. Here I am noble; I am _boyar_; the common people know me,
line = 767 | 1 | and I am master. But a stranger in a strange land, he is no one; men
line = 768 | 1 | know him not--and to know not is to care not for. I am content if I am
line = 769 | 1 | like the rest, so that no man stops if he see me, or pause in his
line = 770 | 1 | speaking if he hear my words, 'Ha, ha! a stranger!' I have been so long
line = 771 | 1 | master that I would be master still--or at least that none other should
line = 772 | 1 | be master of me. You come to me not alone as agent of my friend Peter
line = 773 | 1 | Hawkins, of Exeter, to tell me all about my new estate in London. You
line = 774 | 1 | shall, I trust, rest here with me awhile, so that by our talking I may
line = 775 | 1 | learn the English intonation; and I would that you tell me when I make
line = 776 | 1 | error, even of the smallest, in my speaking. I am sorry that I had to be
line = 777 | 1 | away so long to-day; but you will, I know, forgive one who has so many
line = 778 | 1 | important affairs in hand."
line = 779 | 1 | 
line = 780 | 1 | of its curves. They have, for the first stages, two men to ride and lead
line = 781 | 1 | their spare horses--four in all, so as not to excite curiosity. When
line = 782 | 1 | they dismiss the men, which shall be shortly, they shall themselves look
line = 783 | 1 | after the horses. It may be necessary for us to join forces; if so they
line = 784 | 1 | can mount our whole party. One of the saddles has a movable horn, and
line = 785 | 1 | can be easily adapted for Mina, if required.
line = 786 | 1 | 
line = 787 | 1 | It is a wild adventure we are on. Here, as we are rushing along through
line = 788 | 1 | the darkness, with the cold from the river seeming to rise up and strike
line = 789 | 1 | us; with all the mysterious voices of the night around us, it all comes
line = 790 | 1 | home. We seem to be drifting into unknown places and unknown ways; into
line = 791 | 1 | a whole world of dark and dreadful things. Godalming is shutting the
line = 792 | 1 | furnace door....
line = 793 | 1 | 
line = 794 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 795 | 1 | 
line = 796 | 1 | _31 October._--Still hurrying along. The day has come, and Godalming is
line = 797 | 1 | sleeping. I am on watch. The morning is bitterly cold; the furnace heat
line = 798 | 1 | is grateful, though we have heavy fur coats. As yet we have passed only
line = 799 | 1 | a few open boats, but none of them had on board any box or package of
line = 800 | 1 | anything like the size of the one we seek. The men were scared every
line = 801 | 1 | time we turned our electric lamp on them, and fell on their knees and
line = 802 | 1 | prayed.
line = 803 | 1 | 
line = 804 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 805 | 1 | 
line = 806 | 1 | _1 November, evening._--No news all day; we have found nothing of the
line = 807 | 1 | kind we seek. We have now passed into the Bistritza; and if we are wrong
line = 808 | 1 | in our surmise our chance is gone. We have over-hauled every boat, big
line = 809 | 1 | and little. Early this morning, one crew took us for a Government boat,
line = 810 | 1 | and treated us accordingly. We saw in this a way of smoothing matters,
line = 811 | 1 | so at Fundu, where the Bistritza runs into the Sereth, we got a
line = 812 | 1 | Roumanian flag which we now fly conspicuously. With every boat which we
line = 813 | 1 | have over-hauled since then this trick has succeeded; we have had every
line = 814 | 1 | deference shown to us, and not once any objection to whatever we chose
line = 815 | 1 | to ask or do. Some of the Slovaks tell us that a big boat passed them,
line = 816 | 1 | going at more than usual speed as she had a double crew on board. This
line = 817 | 1 | was before they came to Fundu, so they could not tell us whether the
line = 818 | 1 | boat turned into the Bistritza or continued on up the Sereth. At Fundu
line = 819 | 1 | we could not hear of any such boat, so she must have passed there in the
line = 820 | 1 | night. I am feeling very sleepy; the cold is perhaps beginning to tell
line = 821 | 1 | upon me, and nature must have rest some time. Godalming insists that he
line = 822 | 1 | shall keep the first watch. God bless him for all his goodness to poor
line = 823 | 1 | dear Mina and me.
line = 824 | 1 | 
line = 825 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 826 | 1 | 
line = 827 | 1 | _2 November, morning._--It is broad daylight. That good fellow would not
line = 828 | 1 | wake me. He says it would have been a sin to, for I slept peacefully and
line = 829 | 1 | was forgetting my trouble. It seems brutally selfish to me to have slept
line = 830 | 1 | so long, and let him watch all night; but he was quite right. I am a new
line = 831 | 1 | man this morning; and, as I sit here and watch him sleeping, I can do
line = 832 | 1 | all that is necessary both as to minding the engine, steering, and
line = 833 | 1 | keeping watch. I can feel that my strength and energy are coming back to
line = 834 | 1 | me. I wonder where Mina is now, and Van Helsing. They should have got to
line = 835 | 1 | Veresti about noon on Wednesday. It would take them some time to get the
line = 836 | 1 | carriage and horses; so if they had started and travelled hard, they
line = 837 | 1 | would be about now at the Borgo Pass. God guide and help them! I am
line = 838 | 1 | afraid to think what may happen. If we could only go faster! but we
line = 839 | 1 | cannot; the engines are throbbing and doing their utmost. I wonder how
line = 840 | 1 | Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris are getting on. There seem to be endless
line = 841 | 1 | streams running down the mountains into this river, but as none of them
line = 842 | 1 | are very large--at present, at all events, though they are terrible
line = 843 | 1 | doubtless in winter and when the snow melts--the horsemen may not have
line = 844 | 1 | met much obstruction. I hope that before we get to Strasba we may see
line = 845 | 1 | them; for if by that time we have not overtaken the Count, it may be
line = 846 | 1 | necessary to take counsel together what to do next.
line = 847 | 1 | 
line = 848 | 1 | 
line = 849 | 1 | _Dr. Seward's Diary._
line = 850 | 1 | 
line = 851 | 1 | _2 November._--Three days on the road. No news, and no time to write it
line = 852 | 1 | if there had been, for every moment is precious. We have had only the
line = 853 | 1 | rest needful for the horses; but we are both bearing it wonderfully.
line = 854 | 1 | Those adventurous days of ours are turning up useful. We must push on;
line = 855 | 1 | we shall never feel happy till we get the launch in sight again.
line = 856 | 1 | 
line = 857 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 858 | 1 | 
line = 859 | 1 | _3 November._--We heard at Fundu that the launch had gone up the
line = 860 | 1 | Bistritza. I wish it wasn't so cold. There are signs of snow coming; and
line = 861 | 1 | if it falls heavy it will stop us. In such case we must get a sledge and
line = 862 | 1 | go on, Russian fashion.
line = 863 | 1 | 
line = 864 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 865 | 1 | 
line = 866 | 1 | _4 November._--To-day we heard of the launch having been detained by an
line = 867 | 1 | accident when trying to force a way up the rapids. The Slovak boats get
line = 868 | 1 | up all right, by aid of a rope and steering with knowledge. Some went up
line = 869 | 1 | only a few hours before. Godalming is an amateur fitter himself, and
line = 870 | 1 | evidently it was he who put the launch in trim again. Finally, they got
line = 871 | 1 | up the rapids all right, with local help, and are off on the chase
line = 872 | 1 | afresh. I fear that the boat is not any better for the accident; the
line = 873 | 1 | peasantry tell us that after she got upon smooth water again, she kept
line = 874 | 1 | stopping every now and again so long as she was in sight. We must push
line = 875 | 1 | on harder than ever; our help may be wanted soon.
line = 876 | 1 | 
line = 877 | 1 | 
line = 878 | 1 | _Mina Harker's Journal._
line = 879 | 1 | 
line = 880 | 1 | _31 October._--Arrived at Veresti at noon. The Professor tells me that
line = 881 | 1 | this morning at dawn he could hardly hypnotise me at all, and that all I
line = 882 | 1 | could say was: "dark and quiet." He is off now buying a carriage and
line = 883 | 1 | horses. He says that he will later on try to buy additional horses, so
line = 884 | 1 | that we may be able to change them on the way. We have something more
line = 885 | 1 | than 70 miles before us. The country is lovely, and most interesting; if
line = 886 | 1 | only we were under different conditions, how delightful it would be to
line = 887 | 1 | see it all. If Jonathan and I were driving through it alone what a
line = 888 | 1 | pleasure it would be. To stop and see people, and learn something of
line = 889 | 1 | their life, and to fill our minds and memories with all the colour and
line = 890 | 1 | picturesqueness of the whole wild, beautiful country and the quaint
line = 891 | 1 | people! But, alas!--
line = 892 | 1 | 
line = 893 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 894 | 1 | 
line = 895 | 1 | _Later._--Dr. Van Helsing has returned. He has got the carriage and
line = 896 | 1 | horses; we are to have some dinner, and to start in an hour. The
line = 897 | 1 | landlady is putting us up a huge basket of provisions; it seems enough
line = 898 | 1 | for a company of soldiers. The Professor encourages her, and whispers to
line = 899 | 1 | me that it may be a week before we can get any good food again. He has
line = 900 | 1 | been shopping too, and has sent home such a wonderful lot of fur coats
line = 901 | 1 | and wraps, and all sorts of warm things. There will not be any chance of
line = 902 | 1 | our being cold.
line = 903 | 1 | 
line = 904 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 905 | 1 | 
line = 906 | 1 | We shall soon be off. I am afraid to think what may happen to us. We are
line = 907 | 1 | truly in the hands of God. He alone knows what may be, and I pray Him,
line = 908 | 1 | with all the strength of my sad and humble soul, that He will watch over
line = 909 | 1 | my beloved husband; that whatever may happen, Jonathan may know that I
line = 910 | 1 | loved him and honoured him more than I can say, and that my latest and
line = 911 | 1 | truest thought will be always for him.
line = 912 | 1 | 
line = 913 | 1 | 
line = 914 | 1 | 
line = 915 | 1 | 
line = 916 | 1 | CHAPTER XXVII
line = 917 | 1 | 
line = 918 | 1 | MINA HARKER'S JOURNAL
line = 919 | 1 | 
line = 920 | 1 | 
line = 921 | 1 | _1 November._--All day long we have travelled, and at a good speed. The
line = 922 | 1 | horses seem to know that they are being kindly treated, for they go
line = 923 | 1 | willingly their full stage at best speed. We have now had so many
line = 924 | 1 | changes and find the same thing so constantly that we are encouraged to
line = 925 | 1 | think that the journey will be an easy one. Dr. Van Helsing is laconic;
line = 926 | 1 | he tells the farmers that he is hurrying to Bistritz, and pays them well
line = 927 | 1 | to make the exchange of horses. We get hot soup, or coffee, or tea; and
line = 928 | 1 | off we go. It is a lovely country; full of beauties of all imaginable
line = 929 | 1 | kinds, and the people are brave, and strong, and simple, and seem full
line = 930 | 1 | of nice qualities. They are _very, very_ superstitious. In the first
line = 931 | 1 | house where we stopped, when the woman who served us saw the scar on my
line = 932 | 1 | forehead, she crossed herself and put out two fingers towards me, to
line = 933 | 1 | keep off the evil eye. I believe they went to the trouble of putting an
line = 934 | 1 | extra amount of garlic into our food; and I can't abide garlic. Ever
line = 935 | 1 | since then I have taken care not to take off my hat or veil, and so have
line = 936 | 1 | escaped their suspicions. We are travelling fast, and as we have no
line = 937 | 1 | driver with us to carry tales, we go ahead of scandal; but I daresay
line = 938 | 1 | that fear of the evil eye will follow hard behind us all the way. The
line = 939 | 1 | Professor seems tireless; all day he would not take any rest, though he
line = 940 | 1 | made me sleep for a long spell. At sunset time he hypnotised me, and he
line = 941 | 1 | says that I answered as usual "darkness, lapping water and creaking
line = 942 | 1 | wood"; so our enemy is still on the river. I am afraid to think of
line = 943 | 1 | Jonathan, but somehow I have now no fear for him, or for myself. I write
line = 944 | 1 | this whilst we wait in a farmhouse for the horses to be got ready. Dr.
line = 945 | 1 | Van Helsing is sleeping, Poor dear, he looks very tired and old and
line = 946 | 1 | grey, but his mouth is set as firmly as a conqueror's; even in his sleep
line = 947 | 1 | he is instinct with resolution. When we have well started I must make
line = 948 | 1 | him rest whilst I drive. I shall tell him that we have days before us,
line = 949 | 1 | and we must not break down when most of all his strength will be
line = 950 | 1 | needed.... All is ready; we are off shortly.
line = 951 | 1 | 
line = 952 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 953 | 1 | 
line = 954 | 1 | _2 November, morning._--I was successful, and we took turns driving all
line = 955 | 1 | night; now the day is on us, bright though cold. There is a strange
line = 956 | 1 | heaviness in the air--I say heaviness for want of a better word; I mean
line = 957 | 1 | that it oppresses us both. It is very cold, and only our warm furs keep
line = 958 | 1 | us comfortable. At dawn Van Helsing hypnotised me; he says I answered
line = 959 | 1 | "darkness, creaking wood and roaring water," so the river is changing as
line = 960 | 1 | they ascend. I do hope that my darling will not run any chance of
line = 961 | 1 | danger--more than need be; but we are in God's hands.
line = 962 | 1 | 
line = 963 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 964 | 1 | 
line = 965 | 1 | _2 November, night._--All day long driving. The country gets wilder as
line = 966 | 1 | we go, and the great spurs of the Carpathians, which at Veresti seemed
line = 967 | 1 | so far from us and so low on the horizon, now seem to gather round us
line = 968 | 1 | and tower in front. We both seem in good spirits; I think we make an
line = 969 | 1 | effort each to cheer the other; in the doing so we cheer ourselves. Dr.
line = 970 | 1 | Van Helsing says that by morning we shall reach the Borgo Pass. The
line = 971 | 1 | houses are very few here now, and the Professor says that the last horse
line = 972 | 1 | we got will have to go on with us, as we may not be able to change. He
line = 973 | 1 | got two in addition to the two we changed, so that now we have a rude
line = 974 | 1 | four-in-hand. The dear horses are patient and good, and they give us no
line = 975 | 1 | trouble. We are not worried with other travellers, and so even I can
line = 976 | 1 | drive. We shall get to the Pass in daylight; we do not want to arrive
line = 977 | 1 | before. So we take it easy, and have each a long rest in turn. Oh, what
line = 978 | 1 | will to-morrow bring to us? We go to seek the place where my poor
line = 979 | 1 | darling suffered so much. God grant that we may be guided aright, and
line = 980 | 1 | that He will deign to watch over my husband and those dear to us both,
line = 981 | 1 | and who are in such deadly peril. As for me, I am not worthy in His
line = 982 | 1 | sight. Alas! I am unclean to His eyes, and shall be until He may deign
line = 983 | 1 | to let me stand forth in His sight as one of those who have not incurred
line = 984 | 1 | His wrath.
line = 985 | 1 | 
line = 986 | 1 | 
line = 987 | 1 | _Memorandum by Abraham Van Helsing._
line = 988 | 1 | 
line = 989 | 1 | _4 November._--This to my old and true friend John Seward, M.D., of
line = 990 | 1 | Purfleet, London, in case I may not see him. It may explain. It is
line = 991 | 1 | morning, and I write by a fire which all the night I have kept
line = 992 | 1 | alive--Madam Mina aiding me. It is cold, cold; so cold that the grey
line = 993 | 1 | heavy sky is full of snow, which when it falls will settle for all
line = 994 | 1 | winter as the ground is hardening to receive it. It seems to have
line = 995 | 1 | affected Madam Mina; she has been so heavy of head all day that she was
line = 996 | 1 | not like herself. She sleeps, and sleeps, and sleeps! She who is usual
line = 997 | 1 | so alert, have done literally nothing all the day; she even have lost
line = 998 | 1 | her appetite. She make no entry into her little diary, she who write so
line = 999 | 1 | faithful at every pause. Something whisper to me that all is not well.
line = 1000 | 1 | However, to-night she is more _vif_. Her long sleep all day have refresh
line = 1001 | 1 | and restore her, for now she is all sweet and bright as ever. At sunset
line = 1002 | 1 | I try to hypnotise her, but alas! with no effect; the power has grown
line = 1003 | 1 | less and less with each day, and to-night it fail me altogether. Well,
line = 1004 | 1 | God's will be done--whatever it may be, and whithersoever it may lead!
line = 1005 | 1 | 
line = 1006 | 1 | Now to the historical, for as Madam Mina write not in her stenography, I
line = 1007 | 1 | must, in my cumbrous old fashion, that so each day of us may not go
line = 1008 | 1 | unrecorded.
line = 1009 | 1 | 
line = 1010 | 1 | We got to the Borgo Pass just after sunrise yesterday morning. When I
line = 1011 | 1 | saw the signs of the dawn I got ready for the hypnotism. We stopped our
line = 1012 | 1 | carriage, and got down so that there might be no disturbance. I made a
line = 1013 | 1 | couch with furs, and Madam Mina, lying down, yield herself as usual, but
line = 1014 | 1 | more slow and more short time than ever, to the hypnotic sleep. As
line = 1015 | 1 | before, came the answer: "darkness and the swirling of water." Then she
line = 1016 | 1 | woke, bright and radiant and we go on our way and soon reach the Pass.
line = 1017 | 1 | At this time and place, she become all on fire with zeal; some new
line = 1018 | 1 | guiding power be in her manifested, for she point to a road and say:--
line = 1019 | 1 | 
line = 1020 | 1 | "This is the way."
line = 1021 | 1 | 
line = 1022 | 1 | "How know you it?" I ask.
line = 1023 | 1 | 
line = 1024 | 1 | "Of course I know it," she answer, and with a pause, add: "Have not my
line = 1025 | 1 | Jonathan travelled it and wrote of his travel?"
line = 1026 | 1 | 
line = 1027 | 1 | At first I think somewhat strange, but soon I see that there be only one
line = 1028 | 1 | such by-road. It is used but little, and very different from the coach
line = 1029 | 1 | road from the Bukovina to Bistritz, which is more wide and hard, and
line = 1030 | 1 | more of use.
line = 1031 | 1 | 
line = 1032 | 1 | So we came down this road; when we meet other ways--not always were we
line = 1033 | 1 | sure that they were roads at all, for they be neglect and light snow
line = 1034 | 1 | have fallen--the horses know and they only. I give rein to them, and
line = 1035 | 1 | they go on so patient. By-and-by we find all the things which Jonathan
line = 1036 | 1 | have note in that wonderful diary of him. Then we go on for long, long
line = 1037 | 1 | hours and hours. At the first, I tell Madam Mina to sleep; she try, and
line = 1038 | 1 | she succeed. She sleep all the time; till at the last, I feel myself to
line = 1039 | 1 | suspicious grow, and attempt to wake her. But she sleep on, and I may
line = 1040 | 1 | not wake her though I try. I do not wish to try too hard lest I harm
line = 1041 | 1 | her; for I know that she have suffer much, and sleep at times be
line = 1042 | 1 | all-in-all to her. I think I drowse myself, for all of sudden I feel
line = 1043 | 1 | guilt, as though I have done something; I find myself bolt up, with the
line = 1044 | 1 | reins in my hand, and the good horses go along jog, jog, just as ever. I
line = 1045 | 1 | look down and find Madam Mina still sleep. It is now not far off sunset
line = 1046 | 1 | time, and over the snow the light of the sun flow in big yellow flood,
line = 1047 | 1 | so that we throw great long shadow on where the mountain rise so steep.
line = 1048 | 1 | For we are going up, and up; and all is oh! so wild and rocky, as though
line = 1049 | 1 | it were the end of the world.
line = 1050 | 1 | 
line = 1051 | 1 | Then I arouse Madam Mina. This time she wake with not much trouble, and
line = 1052 | 1 | then I try to put her to hypnotic sleep. But she sleep not, being as
line = 1053 | 1 | though I were not. Still I try and try, till all at once I find her and
line = 1054 | 1 | myself in dark; so I look round, and find that the sun have gone down.
line = 1055 | 1 | Madam Mina laugh, and I turn and look at her. She is now quite awake,
line = 1056 | 1 | and look so well as I never saw her since that night at Carfax when we
line = 1057 | 1 | first enter the Count's house. I am amaze, and not at ease then; but she
line = 1058 | 1 | is so bright and tender and thoughtful for me that I forget all fear. I
line = 1059 | 1 | light a fire, for we have brought supply of wood with us, and she
line = 1060 | 1 | prepare food while I undo the horses and set them, tethered in shelter,
line = 1061 | 1 | to feed. Then when I return to the fire she have my supper ready. I go
line = 1062 | 1 | to help her; but she smile, and tell me that she have eat already--that
line = 1063 | 1 | she was so hungry that she would not wait. I like it not, and I have
line = 1064 | 1 | grave doubts; but I fear to affright her, and so I am silent of it. She
line = 1065 | 1 | help me and I eat alone; and then we wrap in fur and lie beside the
line = 1066 | 1 | fire, and I tell her to sleep while I watch. But presently I forget all
line = 1067 | 1 | of watching; and when I sudden remember that I watch, I find her lying
line = 1068 | 1 | quiet, but awake, and looking at me with so bright eyes. Once, twice
line = 1069 | 1 | more the same occur, and I get much sleep till before morning. When I
line = 1070 | 1 | wake I try to hypnotise her; but alas! though she shut her eyes
line = 1071 | 1 | obedient, she may not sleep. The sun rise up, and up, and up; and then
line = 1072 | 1 | sleep come to her too late, but so heavy that she will not wake. I have
line = 1073 | 1 | to lift her up, and place her sleeping in the carriage when I have
line = 1074 | 1 | harnessed the horses and made all ready. Madam still sleep, and she look
line = 1075 | 1 | in her sleep more healthy and more redder than before. And I like it
line = 1076 | 1 | not. And I am afraid, afraid, afraid!--I am afraid of all things--even
line = 1077 | 1 | to think but I must go on my way. The stake we play for is life and
line = 1078 | 1 | death, or more than these, and we must not flinch.
line = 1079 | 1 | 
line = 1080 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 1081 | 1 | 
line = 1082 | 1 | _5 November, morning._--Let me be accurate in everything, for though you
line = 1083 | 1 | and I have seen some strange things together, you may at the first think
line = 1084 | 1 | that I, Van Helsing, am mad--that the many horrors and the so long
line = 1085 | 1 | strain on nerves has at the last turn my brain.
line = 1086 | 1 | 
line = 1087 | 1 | All yesterday we travel, ever getting closer to the mountains, and
line = 1088 | 1 | moving into a more and more wild and desert land. There are great,
line = 1089 | 1 | frowning precipices and much falling water, and Nature seem to have held
line = 1090 | 1 | sometime her carnival. Madam Mina still sleep and sleep; and though I
line = 1091 | 1 | did have hunger and appeased it, I could not waken her--even for food. I
line = 1092 | 1 | began to fear that the fatal spell of the place was upon her, tainted as
line = 1093 | 1 | she is with that Vampire baptism. "Well," said I to myself, "if it be
line = 1094 | 1 | that she sleep all the day, it shall also be that I do not sleep at
line = 1095 | 1 | night." As we travel on the rough road, for a road of an ancient and
line = 1096 | 1 | imperfect kind there was, I held down my head and slept. Again I waked
line = 1097 | 1 | with a sense of guilt and of time passed, and found Madam Mina still
line = 1098 | 1 | sleeping, and the sun low down. But all was indeed changed; the frowning
line = 1099 | 1 | mountains seemed further away, and we were near the top of a
line = 1100 | 1 | steep-rising hill, on summit of which was such a castle as Jonathan tell
line = 1101 | 1 | of in his diary. At once I exulted and feared; for now, for good or ill,
line = 1102 | 1 | the end was near.
line = 1103 | 1 | 
line = 1104 | 1 | I woke Madam Mina, and again tried to hypnotise her; but alas!
line = 1105 | 1 | unavailing till too late. Then, ere the great dark came upon us--for
line = 1106 | 1 | even after down-sun the heavens reflected the gone sun on the snow, and
line = 1107 | 1 | all was for a time in a great twilight--I took out the horses and fed
line = 1108 | 1 | them in what shelter I could. Then I make a fire; and near it I make
line = 1109 | 1 | Madam Mina, now awake and more charming than ever, sit comfortable amid
line = 1110 | 1 | her rugs. I got ready food: but she would not eat, simply saying that
line = 1111 | 1 | she had not hunger. I did not press her, knowing her unavailingness. But
line = 1112 | 1 | I myself eat, for I must needs now be strong for all. Then, with the
line = 1113 | 1 | fear on me of what might be, I drew a ring so big for her comfort, round
line = 1114 | 1 | where Madam Mina sat; and over the ring I passed some of the wafer, and
line = 1115 | 1 | I broke it fine so that all was well guarded. She sat still all the
line = 1116 | 1 | time--so still as one dead; and she grew whiter and ever whiter till the
line = 1117 | 1 | snow was not more pale; and no word she said. But when I drew near, she
line = 1118 | 1 | clung to me, and I could know that the poor soul shook her from head to
line = 1119 | 1 | feet with a tremor that was pain to feel. I said to her presently, when
line = 1120 | 1 | she had grown more quiet:--
line = 1121 | 1 | 
line = 1122 | 1 | the other operations, and none of us ever shall. Arthur and Quincey went
line = 1123 | 1 | away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here. The
line = 1124 | 1 | moment we were alone in the carriage he gave way to a regular fit of
line = 1125 | 1 | hysterics. He has denied to me since that it was hysterics, and insisted
line = 1126 | 1 | that it was only his sense of humour asserting itself under very
line = 1127 | 1 | terrible conditions. He laughed till he cried, and I had to draw down
line = 1128 | 1 | the blinds lest any one should see us and misjudge; and then he cried,
line = 1129 | 1 | till he laughed again; and laughed and cried together, just as a woman
line = 1130 | 1 | does. I tried to be stern with him, as one is to a woman under the
line = 1131 | 1 | circumstances; but it had no effect. Men and women are so different in
line = 1132 | 1 | manifestations of nervous strength or weakness! Then when his face grew
line = 1133 | 1 | grave and stern again I asked him why his mirth, and why at such a time.
line = 1134 | 1 | His reply was in a way characteristic of him, for it was logical and
line = 1135 | 1 | forceful and mysterious. He said:--
line = 1136 | 1 | 
line = 1137 | 1 | "Ah, you don't comprehend, friend John. Do not think that I am not sad,
line = 1138 | 1 | though I laugh. See, I have cried even when the laugh did choke me. But
line = 1139 | 1 | no more think that I am all sorry when I cry, for the laugh he come
line = 1140 | 1 | just the same. Keep it always with you that laughter who knock at your
line = 1141 | 1 | door and say, 'May I come in?' is not the true laughter. No! he is a
line = 1142 | 1 | king, and he come when and how he like. He ask no person; he choose no
line = 1143 | 1 | time of suitability. He say, 'I am here.' Behold, in example I grieve my
line = 1144 | 1 | heart out for that so sweet young girl; I give my blood for her, though
line = 1145 | 1 | I am old and worn; I give my time, my skill, my sleep; I let my other
line = 1146 | 1 | sufferers want that so she may have all. And yet I can laugh at her very
line = 1147 | 1 | grave--laugh when the clay from the spade of the sexton drop upon her
line = 1148 | 1 | coffin and say 'Thud! thud!' to my heart, till it send back the blood
line = 1149 | 1 | from my cheek. My heart bleed for that poor boy--that dear boy, so of
line = 1150 | 1 | the age of mine own boy had I been so blessed that he live, and with his
line = 1151 | 1 | hair and eyes the same. There, you know now why I love him so. And yet
line = 1152 | 1 | when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my
line = 1153 | 1 | father-heart yearn to him as to no other man--not even to you, friend
line = 1154 | 1 | John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son--yet even
line = 1155 | 1 | at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear,
line = 1156 | 1 | 'Here I am! here I am!' till the blood come dance back and bring some of
line = 1157 | 1 | the sunshine that he carry with him to my cheek. Oh, friend John, it is
line = 1158 | 1 | a strange world, a sad world, a world full of miseries, and woes, and
line = 1159 | 1 | troubles; and yet when King Laugh come he make them all dance to the
line = 1160 | 1 | tune he play. Bleeding hearts, and dry bones of the churchyard, and
line = 1161 | 1 | tears that burn as they fall--all dance together to the music that he
line = 1162 | 1 | make with that smileless mouth of him. And believe me, friend John, that
line = 1163 | 1 | he is good to come, and kind. Ah, we men and women are like ropes drawn
line = 1164 | 1 | tight with strain that pull us different ways. Then tears come; and,
line = 1165 | 1 | like the rain on the ropes, they brace us up, until perhaps the strain
line = 1166 | 1 | become too great, and we break. But King Laugh he come like the
line = 1167 | 1 | sunshine, and he ease off the strain again; and we bear to go on with
line = 1168 | 1 | our labour, what it may be."
line = 1169 | 1 | 
line = 1170 | 1 | I did not like to wound him by pretending not to see his idea; but, as I
line = 1171 | 1 | did not yet understand the cause of his laughter, I asked him. As he
line = 1172 | 1 | answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different
line = 1173 | 1 | tone:--
line = 1174 | 1 | 
line = 1175 | 1 | "Oh, it was the grim irony of it all--this so lovely lady garlanded with
line = 1176 | 1 | flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she
line = 1177 | 1 | were truly dead; she laid in that so fine marble house in that lonely
line = 1178 | 1 | churchyard, where rest so many of her kin, laid there with the mother
line = 1179 | 1 | who loved her, and whom she loved; and that sacred bell going 'Toll!
line = 1180 | 1 | toll! toll!' so sad and slow; and those holy men, with the white
line = 1181 | 1 | garments of the angel, pretending to read books, and yet all the time
line = 1182 | 1 | their eyes never on the page; and all of us with the bowed head. And all
line = 1183 | 1 | for what? She is dead; so! Is it not?"
line = 1184 | 1 | 
line = 1185 | 1 | "Well, for the life of me, Professor," I said, "I can't see anything to
line = 1186 | 1 | laugh at in all that. Why, your explanation makes it a harder puzzle
line = 1187 | 1 | than before. But even if the burial service was comic, what about poor
line = 1188 | 1 | Art and his trouble? Why, his heart was simply breaking."
line = 1189 | 1 | 
line = 1190 | 1 | "Just so. Said he not that the transfusion of his blood to her veins had
line = 1191 | 1 | made her truly his bride?"
line = 1192 | 1 | 
line = 1193 | 1 | "Yes, and it was a sweet and comforting idea for him."
line = 1194 | 1 | 
line = 1195 | 1 | "Quite so. But there was a difficulty, friend John. If so that, then
line = 1196 | 1 | what about the others? Ho, ho! Then this so sweet maid is a polyandrist,
line = 1197 | 1 | and me, with my poor wife dead to me, but alive by Church's law, though
line = 1198 | 1 | no wits, all gone--even I, who am faithful husband to this now-no-wife,
line = 1199 | 1 | am bigamist."
line = 1200 | 1 | 
line = 1201 | 1 | "I don't see where the joke comes in there either!" I said; and I did
line = 1202 | 1 | not feel particularly pleased with him for saying such things. He laid
line = 1203 | 1 | his hand on my arm, and said:--
line = 1204 | 1 | 
line = 1205 | 1 | "Friend John, forgive me if I pain. I showed not my feeling to others
line = 1206 | 1 | when it would wound, but only to you, my old friend, whom I can trust.
line = 1207 | 1 | If you could have looked into my very heart then when I want to laugh;
line = 1208 | 1 | if you could have done so when the laugh arrived; if you could do so
line = 1209 | 1 | now, when King Laugh have pack up his crown, and all that is to him--for
line = 1210 | 1 | he go far, far away from me, and for a long, long time--maybe you would
line = 1211 | 1 | perhaps pity me the most of all."
line = 1212 | 1 | 
line = 1213 | 1 | I was touched by the tenderness of his tone, and asked why.
line = 1214 | 1 | 
line = 1215 | 1 | "Because I know!"
line = 1216 | 1 | 
line = 1217 | 1 | And now we are all scattered; and for many a long day loneliness will
line = 1218 | 1 | sit over our roofs with brooding wings. Lucy lies in the tomb of her
line = 1219 | 1 | kin, a lordly death-house in a lonely churchyard, away from teeming
line = 1220 | 1 | London; where the air is fresh, and the sun rises over Hampstead Hill,
line = 1221 | 1 | and where wild flowers grow of their own accord.
line = 1222 | 1 | 
line = 1223 | 1 | So I can finish this diary; and God only knows if I shall ever begin
line = 1224 | 1 | another. If I do, or if I even open this again, it will be to deal with
line = 1225 | 1 | different people and different themes; for here at the end, where the
line = 1226 | 1 | romance of my life is told, ere I go back to take up the thread of my
line = 1227 | 1 | life-work, I say sadly and without hope,
line = 1228 | 1 | 
line = 1229 | 1 |                         "FINIS."
line = 1230 | 1 | 
line = 1231 | 1 | 
line = 1232 | 1 | _"The Westminster Gazette," 25 September._
line = 1233 | 1 | 
line = 1234 | 1 |                           A HAMPSTEAD MYSTERY.
line = 1235 | 1 | 
line = 1236 | 1 | 
line = 1237 | 1 | The neighbourhood of Hampstead is just at present exercised with a
line = 1238 | 1 | series of events which seem to run on lines parallel to those of what
line = 1239 | 1 | was known to the writers of headlines as "The Kensington Horror," or
line = 1240 | 1 | "The Stabbing Woman," or "The Woman in Black." During the past two or
line = 1241 | 1 | three days several cases have occurred of young children straying from
line = 1242 | 1 | home or neglecting to return from their playing on the Heath. In all
line = 1243 | 1 | these cases the children were too young to give any properly
line = 1244 | 1 | intelligible account of themselves, but the consensus of their excuses
line = 1245 | 1 | is that they had been with a "bloofer lady." It has always been late in
line = 1246 | 1 | the evening when they have been missed, and on two occasions the
line = 1247 | 1 | children have not been found until early in the following morning. It is
line = 1248 | 1 | generally supposed in the neighbourhood that, as the first child missed
line = 1249 | 1 | gave as his reason for being away that a "bloofer lady" had asked him to
line = 1250 | 1 | come for a walk, the others had picked up the phrase and used it as
line = 1251 | 1 | occasion served. This is the more natural as the favourite game of the
line = 1252 | 1 | little ones at present is luring each other away by wiles. A
line = 1253 | 1 | correspondent writes us that to see some of the tiny tots pretending to
line = 1254 | 1 | be the "bloofer lady" is supremely funny. Some of our caricaturists
line = 1255 | 1 | might, he says, take a lesson in the irony of grotesque by comparing the
line = 1256 | 1 | reality and the picture. It is only in accordance with general
line = 1257 | 1 | principles of human nature that the "bloofer lady" should be the popular
line = 1258 | 1 | rôle at these _al fresco_ performances. Our correspondent naïvely says
line = 1259 | 1 | that even Ellen Terry could not be so winningly attractive as some of
line = 1260 | 1 | these grubby-faced little children pretend--and even imagine
line = 1261 | 1 | themselves--to be.
line = 1262 | 1 | 
line = 1263 | 1 | There is, however, possibly a serious side to the question, for some of
line = 1264 | 1 | the children, indeed all who have been missed at night, have been
line = 1265 | 1 | slightly torn or wounded in the throat. The wounds seem such as might be
line = 1266 | 1 | made by a rat or a small dog, and although of not much importance
line = 1267 | 1 | individually, would tend to show that whatever animal inflicts them has
line = 1268 | 1 | a system or method of its own. The police of the division have been
line = 1269 | 1 | instructed to keep a sharp look-out for straying children, especially
line = 1270 | 1 | when very young, in and around Hampstead Heath, and for any stray dog
line = 1271 | 1 | which may be about.
line = 1272 | 1 | 
line = 1273 | 1 | 
line = 1274 | 1 |                _"The Westminster Gazette," 25 September._
line = 1275 | 1 | 
line = 1276 | 1 |                             _Extra Special._
line = 1277 | 1 | 
line = 1278 | 1 |                          THE HAMPSTEAD HORROR.
line = 1279 | 1 | 
line = 1280 | 1 |                          ANOTHER CHILD INJURED.
line = 1281 | 1 | 
line = 1282 | 1 |                          _The "Bloofer Lady."_
line = 1283 | 1 | 
line = 1284 | 1 | We have just received intelligence that another child, missed last
line = 1285 | 1 | night, was only discovered late in the morning under a furze bush at the
line = 1286 | 1 | Shooter's Hill side of Hampstead Heath, which is, perhaps, less
line = 1287 | 1 | frequented than the other parts. It has the same tiny wound in the
line = 1288 | 1 | throat as has been noticed in other cases. It was terribly weak, and
line = 1289 | 1 | looked quite emaciated. It too, when partially restored, had the common
line = 1290 | 1 | story to tell of being lured away by the "bloofer lady."
line = 1291 | 1 | 
line = 1292 | 1 | 
line = 1293 | 1 | 
line = 1294 | 1 | 
line = 1295 | 1 | CHAPTER XIV
line = 1296 | 1 | 
line = 1297 | 1 | MINA HARKER'S JOURNAL
line = 1298 | 1 | 
line = 1299 | 1 | 
line = 1300 | 1 | _23 September_.--Jonathan is better after a bad night. I am so glad that
line = 1301 | 1 | he has plenty of work to do, for that keeps his mind off the terrible
line = 1302 | 1 | things; and oh, I am rejoiced that he is not now weighed down with the
line = 1303 | 1 | responsibility of his new position. I knew he would be true to himself,
line = 1304 | 1 | and now how proud I am to see my Jonathan rising to the height of his
line = 1305 | 1 | advancement and keeping pace in all ways with the duties that come upon
line = 1306 | 1 | him. He will be away all day till late, for he said he could not lunch
line = 1307 | 1 | at home. My household work is done, so I shall take his foreign journal,
line = 1308 | 1 | and lock myself up in my room and read it....
line = 1309 | 1 | 
line = 1310 | 1 | 
line = 1311 | 1 | _24 September_.--I hadn't the heart to write last night; that terrible
line = 1312 | 1 | record of Jonathan's upset me so. Poor dear! How he must have suffered,
line = 1313 | 1 | whether it be true or only imagination. I wonder if there is any truth
line = 1314 | 1 | in it at all. Did he get his brain fever, and then write all those
line = 1315 | 1 | terrible things, or had he some cause for it all? I suppose I shall
line = 1316 | 1 | never know, for I dare not open the subject to him.... And yet that man
line = 1317 | 1 | we saw yesterday! He seemed quite certain of him.... Poor fellow! I
line = 1318 | 1 | suppose it was the funeral upset him and sent his mind back on some
line = 1319 | 1 | train of thought.... He believes it all himself. I remember how on our
line = 1320 | 1 | wedding-day he said: "Unless some solemn duty come upon me to go back to
line = 1321 | 1 | the bitter hours, asleep or awake, mad or sane." There seems to be
line = 1322 | 1 | through it all some thread of continuity.... That fearful Count was
line = 1323 | 1 | coming to London.... If it should be, and he came to London, with his
line = 1324 | 1 | teeming millions.... There may be a solemn duty; and if it come we must
line = 1325 | 1 | not shrink from it.... I shall be prepared. I shall get my typewriter
line = 1326 | 1 | this very hour and begin transcribing. Then we shall be ready for other
line = 1327 | 1 | eyes if required. And if it be wanted; then, perhaps, if I am ready,
line = 1328 | 1 | poor Jonathan may not be upset, for I can speak for him and never let
line = 1329 | 1 | him be troubled or worried with it at all. If ever Jonathan quite gets
line = 1330 | 1 | over the nervousness he may want to tell me of it all, and I can ask him
line = 1331 | 1 | questions and find out things, and see how I may comfort him.
line = 1332 | 1 | 
line = 1333 | 1 | 
line = 1334 | 1 | _Letter, Van Helsing to Mrs. Harker._
line = 1335 | 1 | 
line = 1336 | 1 | "_24 September._
line = 1337 | 1 | 
line = 1338 | 1 | (_Confidence_)
line = 1339 | 1 | 
line = 1340 | 1 | "Dear Madam,--
line = 1341 | 1 | 
line = 1342 | 1 | "I pray you to pardon my writing, in that I am so far friend as that I
line = 1343 | 1 | sent to you sad news of Miss Lucy Westenra's death. By the kindness of
line = 1344 | 1 | Lord Godalming, I am empowered to read her letters and papers, for I am
line = 1345 | 1 | deeply concerned about certain matters vitally important. In them I find
line = 1346 | 1 | some letters from you, which show how great friends you were and how you
line = 1347 | 1 | love her. Oh, Madam Mina, by that love, I implore you, help me. It is
line = 1348 | 1 | for others' good that I ask--to redress great wrong, and to lift much
line = 1349 | 1 | and terrible troubles--that may be more great than you can know. May it
line = 1350 | 1 | be that I see you? You can trust me. I am friend of Dr. John Seward and
line = 1351 | 1 | of Lord Godalming (that was Arthur of Miss Lucy). I must keep it private
line = 1352 | 1 | for the present from all. I should come to Exeter to see you at once if
line = 1353 | 1 | you tell me I am privilege to come, and where and when. I implore your
line = 1354 | 1 | pardon, madam. I have read your letters to poor Lucy, and know how good
line = 1355 | 1 | you are and how your husband suffer; so I pray you, if it may be,
line = 1356 | 1 | enlighten him not, lest it may harm. Again your pardon, and forgive me.
line = 1357 | 1 | 
line = 1358 | 1 | "VAN HELSING."
line = 1359 | 1 | 
line = 1360 | 1 | 
line = 1361 | 1 | _Telegram, Mrs. Harker to Van Helsing._
line = 1362 | 1 | 
line = 1363 | 1 | "_25 September._--Come to-day by quarter-past ten train if you can catch
line = 1364 | 1 | it. Can see you any time you call.
line = 1365 | 1 | 
line = 1366 | 1 | "WILHELMINA HARKER."
line = 1367 | 1 | 
line = 1368 | 1 | MINA HARKER'S JOURNAL.
line = 1369 | 1 | 
line = 1370 | 1 | _25 September._--I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time
line = 1371 | 1 | draws near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that
line = 1372 | 1 | it will throw some light upon Jonathan's sad experience; and as he
line = 1373 | 1 | attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about
line = 1374 | 1 | her. That is the reason of his coming; it is concerning Lucy and her
line = 1375 | 1 | sleep-walking, and not about Jonathan. Then I shall never know the real
line = 1376 | 1 | truth now! How silly I am. That awful journal gets hold of my
line = 1377 | 1 | imagination and tinges everything with something of its own colour. Of
line = 1378 | 1 | course it is about Lucy. That habit came back to the poor dear, and that
line = 1379 | 1 | awful night on the cliff must have made her ill. I had almost forgotten
line = 1380 | 1 | in my own affairs how ill she was afterwards. She must have told him
line = 1381 | 1 | of her sleep-walking adventure on the cliff, and that I knew all about
line = 1382 | 1 | it; and now he wants me to tell him what she knows, so that he may
line = 1383 | 1 | understand. I hope I did right in not saying anything of it to Mrs.
line = 1384 | 1 | Westenra; I should never forgive myself if any act of mine, were it even
line = 1385 | 1 | a negative one, brought harm on poor dear Lucy. I hope, too, Dr. Van
line = 1386 | 1 | Helsing will not blame me; I have had so much trouble and anxiety of
line = 1387 | 1 | late that I feel I cannot bear more just at present.
line = 1388 | 1 | 
line = 1389 | 1 | I suppose a cry does us all good at times--clears the air as other rain
line = 1390 | 1 | does. Perhaps it was reading the journal yesterday that upset me, and
line = 1391 | 1 | then Jonathan went away this morning to stay away from me a whole day
line = 1392 | 1 | and night, the first time we have been parted since our marriage. I do
line = 1393 | 1 | hope the dear fellow will take care of himself, and that nothing will
line = 1394 | 1 | occur to upset him. It is two o'clock, and the doctor will be here soon
line = 1395 | 1 | now. I shall say nothing of Jonathan's journal unless he asks me. I am
line = 1396 | 1 | so glad I have type-written out my own journal, so that, in case he asks
line = 1397 | 1 | about Lucy, I can hand it to him; it will save much questioning.
line = 1398 | 1 | 
line = 1399 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 1400 | 1 | 
line = 1401 | 1 | _Later._--He has come and gone. Oh, what a strange meeting, and how it
line = 1402 | 1 | all makes my head whirl round! I feel like one in a dream. Can it be all
line = 1403 | 1 | possible, or even a part of it? If I had not read Jonathan's journal
line = 1404 | 1 | first, I should never have accepted even a possibility. Poor, poor, dear
line = 1405 | 1 | Jonathan! How he must have suffered. Please the good God, all this may
line = 1406 | 1 | not upset him again. I shall try to save him from it; but it may be even
line = 1407 | 1 | a consolation and a help to him--terrible though it be and awful in its
line = 1408 | 1 | consequences--to know for certain that his eyes and ears and brain did
line = 1409 | 1 | not deceive him, and that it is all true. It may be that it is the doubt
line = 1410 | 1 | which haunts him; that when the doubt is removed, no matter
line = 1411 | 1 | which--waking or dreaming--may prove the truth, he will be more
line = 1412 | 1 | satisfied and better able to bear the shock. Dr. Van Helsing must be a
line = 1413 | 1 | good man as well as a clever one if he is Arthur's friend and Dr.
line = 1414 | 1 | Seward's, and if they brought him all the way from Holland to look after
line = 1415 | 1 | Lucy. I feel from having seen him that he _is_ good and kind and of a
line = 1416 | 1 | noble nature. When he comes to-morrow I shall ask him about Jonathan;
line = 1417 | 1 | and then, please God, all this sorrow and anxiety may lead to a good
line = 1418 | 1 | end. I used to think I would like to practise interviewing; Jonathan's
line = 1419 | 1 | friend on "The Exeter News" told him that memory was everything in such
line = 1420 | 1 | work--that you must be able to put down exactly almost every word
line = 1421 | 1 | spoken, even if you had to refine some of it afterwards. Here was a rare
line = 1422 | 1 | interview; I shall try to record it _verbatim_.
line = 1423 | 1 | 
line = 1424 | 1 | It was half-past two o'clock when the knock came. I took my courage _à
line = 1425 | 1 | deux mains_ and waited. In a few minutes Mary opened the door, and
line = 1426 | 1 | announced "Dr. Van Helsing."
line = 1427 | 1 | 
line = 1428 | 1 | I rose and bowed, and he came towards me; a man of medium weight,
line = 1429 | 1 | strongly built, with his shoulders set back over a broad, deep chest and
line = 1430 | 1 | a neck well balanced on the trunk as the head is on the neck. The poise
line = 1431 | 1 | of the head strikes one at once as indicative of thought and power; the
line = 1432 | 1 | head is noble, well-sized, broad, and large behind the ears. The face,
line = 1433 | 1 | clean-shaven, shows a hard, square chin, a large, resolute, mobile
line = 1434 | 1 | mouth, a good-sized nose, rather straight, but with quick, sensitive
line = 1435 | 1 | nostrils, that seem to broaden as the big, bushy brows come down and the
line = 1436 | 1 | mouth tightens. The forehead is broad and fine, rising at first almost
line = 1437 | 1 | straight and then sloping back above two bumps or ridges wide apart;
line = 1438 | 1 | such a forehead that the reddish hair cannot possibly tumble over it,
line = 1439 | 1 | but falls naturally back and to the sides. Big, dark blue eyes are set
line = 1440 | 1 | widely apart, and are quick and tender or stern with the man's moods. He
line = 1441 | 1 | said to me:--
line = 1442 | 1 | 
line = 1443 | 1 | "Mrs. Harker, is it not?" I bowed assent.
line = 1444 | 1 | 
line = 1445 | 1 | "That was Miss Mina Murray?" Again I assented.
line = 1446 | 1 | 
line = 1447 | 1 | "It is Mina Murray that I came to see that was friend of that poor dear
line = 1448 | 1 | child Lucy Westenra. Madam Mina, it is on account of the dead I come."
line = 1449 | 1 | 
line = 1450 | 1 | "Sir," I said, "you could have no better claim on me than that you were
line = 1451 | 1 | a friend and helper of Lucy Westenra." And I held out my hand. He took
line = 1452 | 1 | it and said tenderly:--
line = 1453 | 1 | 
line = 1454 | 1 | "Oh, Madam Mina, I knew that the friend of that poor lily girl must be
line = 1455 | 1 | good, but I had yet to learn----" He finished his speech with a courtly
line = 1456 | 1 | bow. I asked him what it was that he wanted to see me about, so he at
line = 1457 | 1 | once began:--
line = 1458 | 1 | 
line = 1459 | 1 | "I have read your letters to Miss Lucy. Forgive me, but I had to begin
line = 1460 | 1 | to inquire somewhere, and there was none to ask. I know that you were
line = 1461 | 1 | with her at Whitby. She sometimes kept a diary--you need not look
line = 1462 | 1 | surprised, Madam Mina; it was begun after you had left, and was in
line = 1463 | 1 | imitation of you--and in that diary she traces by inference certain
line = 1464 | 1 | things to a sleep-walking in which she puts down that you saved her. In
line = 1465 | 1 | great perplexity then I come to you, and ask you out of your so much
line = 1466 | 1 | kindness to tell me all of it that you can remember."
line = 1467 | 1 | 
line = 1468 | 1 | "I can tell you, I think, Dr. Van Helsing, all about it."
line = 1469 | 1 | 
line = 1470 | 1 | "Ah, then you have good memory for facts, for details? It is not always
line = 1471 | 1 | so with young ladies."
line = 1472 | 1 | 
line = 1473 | 1 | "No, doctor, but I wrote it all down at the time. I can show it to you
line = 1474 | 1 | if you like."
line = 1475 | 1 | 
line = 1476 | 1 | "Oh, Madam Mina, I will be grateful; you will do me much favour." I
line = 1477 | 1 | could not resist the temptation of mystifying him a bit--I suppose it is
line = 1478 | 1 | some of the taste of the original apple that remains still in our
line = 1479 | 1 | mouths--so I handed him the shorthand diary. He took it with a grateful
line = 1480 | 1 | bow, and said:--
line = 1481 | 1 | 
line = 1482 | 1 | "May I read it?"
line = 1483 | 1 | 
line = 1484 | 1 | "If you wish," I answered as demurely as I could. He opened it, and for
line = 1485 | 1 | an instant his face fell. Then he stood up and bowed.
line = 1486 | 1 | 
line = 1487 | 1 | "Oh, you so clever woman!" he said. "I knew long that Mr. Jonathan was a
line = 1488 | 1 | man of much thankfulness; but see, his wife have all the good things.
line = 1489 | 1 | And will you not so much honour me and so help me as to read it for me?
line = 1490 | 1 | Alas! I know not the shorthand." By this time my little joke was over,
line = 1491 | 1 | and I was almost ashamed; so I took the typewritten copy from my
line = 1492 | 1 | workbasket and handed it to him.
line = 1493 | 1 | 
line = 1494 | 1 | "Forgive me," I said: "I could not help it; but I had been thinking that
line = 1495 | 1 | it was of dear Lucy that you wished to ask, and so that you might not
line = 1496 | 1 | have time to wait--not on my account, but because I know your time must
line = 1497 | 1 | be precious--I have written it out on the typewriter for you."
line = 1498 | 1 | 
line = 1499 | 1 | He took it and his eyes glistened. "You are so good," he said. "And may
line = 1500 | 1 | I read it now? I may want to ask you some things when I have read."
line = 1501 | 1 | 
line = 1502 | 1 | "By all means," I said, "read it over whilst I order lunch; and then you
line = 1503 | 1 | can ask me questions whilst we eat." He bowed and settled himself in a
line = 1504 | 1 | chair with his back to the light, and became absorbed in the papers,
line = 1505 | 1 | whilst I went to see after lunch chiefly in order that he might not be
line = 1506 | 1 | disturbed. When I came back, I found him walking hurriedly up and down
line = 1507 | 1 | the room, his face all ablaze with excitement. He rushed up to me and
line = 1508 | 1 | took me by both hands.
line = 1509 | 1 | 
line = 1510 | 1 | "Oh, Madam Mina," he said, "how can I say what I owe to you? This paper
line = 1511 | 1 | is as sunshine. It opens the gate to me. I am daze, I am dazzle, with so
line = 1512 | 1 | much light, and yet clouds roll in behind the light every time. But that
line = 1513 | 1 | you do not, cannot, comprehend. Oh, but I am grateful to you, you so
line = 1514 | 1 | clever woman. Madam"--he said this very solemnly--"if ever Abraham Van
line = 1515 | 1 | Helsing can do anything for you or yours, I trust you will let me know.
line = 1516 | 1 | It will be pleasure and delight if I may serve you as a friend; as a
line = 1517 | 1 | friend, but all I have ever learned, all I can ever do, shall be for you
line = 1518 | 1 | and those you love. There are darknesses in life, and there are lights;
line = 1519 | 1 | you are one of the lights. You will have happy life and good life, and
line = 1520 | 1 | your husband will be blessed in you."
line = 1521 | 1 | 
line = 1522 | 1 | "But, doctor, you praise me too much, and--and you do not know me."
line = 1523 | 1 | 
line = 1524 | 1 | "Not know you--I, who am old, and who have studied all my life men and
line = 1525 | 1 | women; I, who have made my specialty the brain and all that belongs to
line = 1526 | 1 | him and all that follow from him! And I have read your diary that you
line = 1527 | 1 | have so goodly written for me, and which breathes out truth in every
line = 1528 | 1 | line. I, who have read your so sweet letter to poor Lucy of your
line = 1529 | 1 | marriage and your trust, not know you! Oh, Madam Mina, good women tell
line = 1530 | 1 | all their lives, and by day and by hour and by minute, such things that
line = 1531 | 1 | angels can read; and we men who wish to know have in us something of
line = 1532 | 1 | angels' eyes. Your husband is noble nature, and you are noble too, for
line = 1533 | 1 | you trust, and trust cannot be where there is mean nature. And your
line = 1534 | 1 | husband--tell me of him. Is he quite well? Is all that fever gone, and
line = 1535 | 1 | is he strong and hearty?" I saw here an opening to ask him about
line = 1536 | 1 | Jonathan, so I said:--
line = 1537 | 1 | 
line = 1538 | 1 | "He was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins's
line = 1539 | 1 | death." He interrupted:--
line = 1540 | 1 | 
line = 1541 | 1 | "Oh, yes, I know, I know. I have read your last two letters." I went
line = 1542 | 1 | on:--
line = 1543 | 1 | 
line = 1544 | 1 | "I suppose this upset him, for when we were in town on Thursday last he
line = 1545 | 1 | had a sort of shock."
line = 1546 | 1 | 
line = 1547 | 1 | "A shock, and after brain fever so soon! That was not good. What kind of
line = 1548 | 1 | a shock was it?"
line = 1549 | 1 | 
line = 1550 | 1 | "He thought he saw some one who recalled something terrible, something
line = 1551 | 1 | which led to his brain fever." And here the whole thing seemed to
line = 1552 | 1 | overwhelm me in a rush. The pity for Jonathan, the horror which he
line = 1553 | 1 | experienced, the whole fearful mystery of his diary, and the fear that
line = 1554 | 1 | has been brooding over me ever since, all came in a tumult. I suppose I
line = 1555 | 1 | was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to
line = 1556 | 1 | him, and implored him to make my husband well again. He took my hands
line = 1557 | 1 | and raised me up, and made me sit on the sofa, and sat by me; he held my
line = 1558 | 1 | hand in his, and said to me with, oh, such infinite sweetness:--
line = 1559 | 1 | 
line = 1560 | 1 | "My life is a barren and lonely one, and so full of work that I have not
line = 1561 | 1 | had much time for friendships; but since I have been summoned to here by
line = 1562 | 1 | my friend John Seward I have known so many good people and seen such
line = 1563 | 1 | nobility that I feel more than ever--and it has grown with my advancing
line = 1564 | 1 | years--the loneliness of my life. Believe, me, then, that I come here
line = 1565 | 1 | full of respect for you, and you have given me hope--hope, not in what I
line = 1566 | 1 | am seeking of, but that there are good women still left to make life
line = 1567 | 1 | happy--good women, whose lives and whose truths may make good lesson for
line = 1568 | 1 | the children that are to be. I am glad, glad, that I may here be of some
line = 1569 | 1 | use to you; for if your husband suffer, he suffer within the range of my
line = 1570 | 1 | study and experience. I promise you that I will gladly do _all_ for him
line = 1571 | 1 | that I can--all to make his life strong and manly, and your life a happy
line = 1572 | 1 | one. Now you must eat. You are overwrought and perhaps over-anxious.
line = 1573 | 1 | Husband Jonathan would not like to see you so pale; and what he like not
line = 1574 | 1 | where he love, is not to his good. Therefore for his sake you must eat
line = 1575 | 1 | and smile. You have told me all about Lucy, and so now we shall not
line = 1576 | 1 | speak of it, lest it distress. I shall stay in Exeter to-night, for I
line = 1577 | 1 | want to think much over what you have told me, and when I have thought I
line = 1578 | 1 | will ask you questions, if I may. And then, too, you will tell me of
line = 1579 | 1 | husband Jonathan's trouble so far as you can, but not yet. You must eat
line = 1580 | 1 | now; afterwards you shall tell me all."
line = 1581 | 1 | 
line = 1582 | 1 | After lunch, when we went back to the drawing-room, he said to me:--
line = 1583 | 1 | 
line = 1584 | 1 | "And now tell me all about him." When it came to speaking to this great
line = 1585 | 1 | learned man, I began to fear that he would think me a weak fool, and
line = 1586 | 1 | Jonathan a madman--that journal is all so strange--and I hesitated to go
line = 1587 | 1 | on. But he was so sweet and kind, and he had promised to help, and I
line = 1588 | 1 | trusted him, so I said:--
line = 1589 | 1 | 
line = 1590 | 1 | "Dr. Van Helsing, what I have to tell you is so queer that you must not
line = 1591 | 1 | laugh at me or at my husband. I have been since yesterday in a sort of
line = 1592 | 1 | fever of doubt; you must be kind to me, and not think me foolish that I
line = 1593 | 1 | have even half believed some very strange things." He reassured me by
line = 1594 | 1 | his manner as well as his words when he said:--
line = 1595 | 1 | 
line = 1596 | 1 | "Oh, my dear, if you only know how strange is the matter regarding which
line = 1597 | 1 | I am here, it is you who would laugh. I have learned not to think little
line = 1598 | 1 | of any one's belief, no matter how strange it be. I have tried to keep
line = 1599 | 1 | an open mind; and it is not the ordinary things of life that could close
line = 1600 | 1 | it, but the strange things, the extraordinary things, the things that
line = 1601 | 1 | make one doubt if they be mad or sane."
line = 1602 | 1 | 
line = 1603 | 1 | "Thank you, thank you, a thousand times! You have taken a weight off my
line = 1604 | 1 | mind. If you will let me, I shall give you a paper to read. It is long,
line = 1605 | 1 | but I have typewritten it out. It will tell you my trouble and
line = 1606 | 1 | Jonathan's. It is the copy of his journal when abroad, and all that
line = 1607 | 1 | happened. I dare not say anything of it; you will read for yourself and
line = 1608 | 1 | judge. And then when I see you, perhaps, you will be very kind and tell
line = 1609 | 1 | me what you think."
line = 1610 | 1 | 
line = 1611 | 1 | "I promise," he said as I gave him the papers; "I shall in the morning,
line = 1612 | 1 | so soon as I can, come to see you and your husband, if I may."
line = 1613 | 1 | 
line = 1614 | 1 | "Jonathan will be here at half-past eleven, and you must come to lunch
line = 1615 | 1 | with us and see him then; you could catch the quick 3:34 train, which
line = 1616 | 1 | will leave you at Paddington before eight." He was surprised at my
line = 1617 | 1 | knowledge of the trains off-hand, but he does not know that I have made
line = 1618 | 1 | up all the trains to and from Exeter, so that I may help Jonathan in
line = 1619 | 1 | case he is in a hurry.
line = 1620 | 1 | 
line = 1621 | 1 | So he took the papers with him and went away, and I sit here
line = 1622 | 1 | thinking--thinking I don't know what.
line = 1623 | 1 | 
line = 1624 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
