line = 1674 | 1 | _Jonathan Harker's Journal._
line = 1675 | 1 | 
line = 1676 | 1 | _26 September._--I thought never to write in this diary again, but the
line = 1677 | 1 | time has come. When I got home last night Mina had supper ready, and
line = 1678 | 1 | when we had supped she told me of Van Helsing's visit, and of her having
line = 1679 | 1 | given him the two diaries copied out, and of how anxious she has been
line = 1680 | 1 | about me. She showed me in the doctor's letter that all I wrote down was
line = 1681 | 1 | true. It seems to have made a new man of me. It was the doubt as to the
line = 1682 | 1 | reality of the whole thing that knocked me over. I felt impotent, and in
line = 1683 | 1 | the dark, and distrustful. But, now that I _know_, I am not afraid, even
line = 1684 | 1 | of the Count. He has succeeded after all, then, in his design in getting
line = 1685 | 1 | to London, and it was he I saw. He has got younger, and how? Van Helsing
line = 1686 | 1 | is the man to unmask him and hunt him out, if he is anything like what
line = 1687 | 1 | Mina says. We sat late, and talked it all over. Mina is dressing, and I
line = 1688 | 1 | shall call at the hotel in a few minutes and bring him over....
line = 1689 | 1 | 
line = 1690 | 1 | He was, I think, surprised to see me. When I came into the room where he
line = 1691 | 1 | was, and introduced myself, he took me by the shoulder, and turned my
line = 1692 | 1 | face round to the light, and said, after a sharp scrutiny:--
line = 1693 | 1 | 
line = 1694 | 1 | "But Madam Mina told me you were ill, that you had had a shock." It was
line = 1695 | 1 | so funny to hear my wife called "Madam Mina" by this kindly,
line = 1696 | 1 | strong-faced old man. I smiled, and said:--
line = 1697 | 1 | 
line = 1698 | 1 | "I _was_ ill, I _have_ had a shock; but you have cured me already."
line = 1699 | 1 | 
line = 1700 | 1 | "And how?"
line = 1701 | 1 | 
line = 1702 | 1 | "By your letter to Mina last night. I was in doubt, and then everything
line = 1703 | 1 | took a hue of unreality, and I did not know what to trust, even the
line = 1704 | 1 | evidence of my own senses. Not knowing what to trust, I did not know
line = 1705 | 1 | what to do; and so had only to keep on working in what had hitherto been
line = 1706 | 1 | the groove of my life. The groove ceased to avail me, and I mistrusted
line = 1707 | 1 | myself. Doctor, you don't know what it is to doubt everything, even
line = 1708 | 1 | yourself. No, you don't; you couldn't with eyebrows like yours." He
line = 1709 | 1 | seemed pleased, and laughed as he said:--
line = 1710 | 1 | 
line = 1711 | 1 | "So! You are physiognomist. I learn more here with each hour. I am with
line = 1712 | 1 | so much pleasure coming to you to breakfast; and, oh, sir, you will
line = 1713 | 1 | pardon praise from an old man, but you are blessed in your wife." I
line = 1714 | 1 | would listen to him go on praising Mina for a day, so I simply nodded
line = 1715 | 1 | and stood silent.
line = 1716 | 1 | 
line = 1717 | 1 | "She is one of God's women, fashioned by His own hand to show us men and
line = 1718 | 1 | other women that there is a heaven where we can enter, and that its
line = 1719 | 1 | light can be here on earth. So true, so sweet, so noble, so little an
line = 1720 | 1 | egoist--and that, let me tell you, is much in this age, so sceptical and
line = 1721 | 1 | selfish. And you, sir--I have read all the letters to poor Miss Lucy,
line = 1722 | 1 | and some of them speak of you, so I know you since some days from the
line = 1723 | 1 | knowing of others; but I have seen your true self since last night. You
line = 1724 | 1 | will give me your hand, will you not? And let us be friends for all our
line = 1725 | 1 | lives."
line = 1726 | 1 | 
line = 1727 | 1 | We shook hands, and he was so earnest and so kind that it made me quite
line = 1728 | 1 | choky.
line = 1729 | 1 | 
