line = 1758 | 1 | the train moved off. This recalled him to himself, and he leaned out of
line = 1759 | 1 | the window and waved his hand, calling out: "Love to Madam Mina; I shall
line = 1760 | 1 | write so soon as ever I can."
line = 1761 | 1 | 
line = 1762 | 1 | 
line = 1763 | 1 | _Dr. Seward's Diary._
line = 1764 | 1 | 
line = 1765 | 1 | _26 September._--Truly there is no such thing as finality. Not a week
line = 1766 | 1 | since I said "Finis," and yet here I am starting fresh again, or rather
line = 1767 | 1 | going on with the same record. Until this afternoon I had no cause to
line = 1768 | 1 | think of what is done. Renfield had become, to all intents, as sane as
line = 1769 | 1 | he ever was. He was already well ahead with his fly business; and he had
line = 1770 | 1 | just started in the spider line also; so he had not been of any trouble
line = 1771 | 1 | to me. I had a letter from Arthur, written on Sunday, and from it I
line = 1772 | 1 | gather that he is bearing up wonderfully well. Quincey Morris is with
line = 1773 | 1 | him, and that is much of a help, for he himself is a bubbling well of
line = 1774 | 1 | good spirits. Quincey wrote me a line too, and from him I hear that
line = 1775 | 1 | Arthur is beginning to recover something of his old buoyancy; so as to
line = 1776 | 1 | them all my mind is at rest. As for myself, I was settling down to my
line = 1777 | 1 | work with the enthusiasm which I used to have for it, so that I might
line = 1778 | 1 | fairly have said that the wound which poor Lucy left on me was becoming
line = 1779 | 1 | cicatrised. Everything is, however, now reopened; and what is to be the
line = 1780 | 1 | end God only knows. I have an idea that Van Helsing thinks he knows,
line = 1781 | 1 | too, but he will only let out enough at a time to whet curiosity. He
line = 1782 | 1 | went to Exeter yesterday, and stayed there all night. To-day he came
line = 1783 | 1 | back, and almost bounded into the room at about half-past five o'clock,
line = 1784 | 1 | and thrust last night's "Westminster Gazette" into my hand.
line = 1785 | 1 | 
line = 1786 | 1 | "What do you think of that?" he asked as he stood back and folded his
line = 1787 | 1 | arms.
line = 1788 | 1 | 
line = 1789 | 1 | I looked over the paper, for I really did not know what he meant; but he
line = 1790 | 1 | took it from me and pointed out a paragraph about children being decoyed
line = 1791 | 1 | away at Hampstead. It did not convey much to me, until I reached a
line = 1792 | 1 | passage where it described small punctured wounds on their throats. An
line = 1793 | 1 | idea struck me, and I looked up. "Well?" he said.
line = 1794 | 1 | 
line = 1795 | 1 | "It is like poor Lucy's."
line = 1796 | 1 | 
line = 1797 | 1 | "And what do you make of it?"
line = 1798 | 1 | 
line = 1799 | 1 | "Simply that there is some cause in common. Whatever it was that injured
line = 1800 | 1 | her has injured them." I did not quite understand his answer:--
line = 1801 | 1 | 
line = 1802 | 1 | "That is true indirectly, but not directly."
line = 1803 | 1 | 
line = 1804 | 1 | "How do you mean, Professor?" I asked. I was a little inclined to take
line = 1805 | 1 | his seriousness lightly--for, after all, four days of rest and freedom
line = 1806 | 1 | from burning, harrowing anxiety does help to restore one's spirits--but
line = 1807 | 1 | when I saw his face, it sobered me. Never, even in the midst of our
line = 1808 | 1 | despair about poor Lucy, had he looked more stern.
line = 1809 | 1 | 
line = 1810 | 1 | "Tell me!" I said. "I can hazard no opinion. I do not know what to
line = 1811 | 1 | think, and I have no data on which to found a conjecture."
line = 1812 | 1 | 
line = 1813 | 1 | "Do you mean to tell me, friend John, that you have no suspicion as to
line = 1814 | 1 | what poor Lucy died of; not after all the hints given, not only by
line = 1815 | 1 | events, but by me?"
line = 1816 | 1 | 
line = 1817 | 1 | "Of nervous prostration following on great loss or waste of blood."
line = 1818 | 1 | 
line = 1819 | 1 | "And how the blood lost or waste?" I shook my head. He stepped over and
line = 1820 | 1 | sat down beside me, and went on:--
line = 1821 | 1 | 
line = 1822 | 1 | "You are clever man, friend John; you reason well, and your wit is bold;
line = 1823 | 1 | but you are too prejudiced. You do not let your eyes see nor your ears
line = 1824 | 1 | hear, and that which is outside your daily life is not of account to
line = 1825 | 1 | you. Do you not think that there are things which you cannot understand,
line = 1826 | 1 | and yet which are; that some people see things that others cannot? But
line = 1827 | 1 | there are things old and new which must not be contemplate by men's
line = 1828 | 1 | eyes, because they know--or think they know--some things which other men
line = 1829 | 1 | have told them. Ah, it is the fault of our science that it wants to
line = 1830 | 1 | explain all; and if it explain not, then it says there is nothing to
line = 1831 | 1 | explain. But yet we see around us every day the growth of new beliefs,
line = 1832 | 1 | which think themselves new; and which are yet but the old, which pretend
line = 1833 | 1 | to be young--like the fine ladies at the opera. I suppose now you do not
line = 1834 | 1 | believe in corporeal transference. No? Nor in materialisation. No? Nor
line = 1835 | 1 | in astral bodies. No? Nor in the reading of thought. No? Nor in
line = 1836 | 1 | hypnotism----"
line = 1837 | 1 | 
line = 1838 | 1 | "Yes," I said. "Charcot has proved that pretty well." He smiled as he
line = 1839 | 1 | went on: "Then you are satisfied as to it. Yes? And of course then you
line = 1840 | 1 | understand how it act, and can follow the mind of the great
line = 1841 | 1 | Charcot--alas that he is no more!--into the very soul of the patient
line = 1842 | 1 | that he influence. No? Then, friend John, am I to take it that you
line = 1843 | 1 | simply accept fact, and are satisfied to let from premise to conclusion
