line = 1845 | 1 | accept the hypnotism and reject the thought reading. Let me tell you, my
line = 1846 | 1 | friend, that there are things done to-day in electrical science which
line = 1847 | 1 | would have been deemed unholy by the very men who discovered
line = 1848 | 1 | electricity--who would themselves not so long before have been burned
line = 1849 | 1 | as wizards. There are always mysteries in life. Why was it that
line = 1850 | 1 | Methuselah lived nine hundred years, and 'Old Parr' one hundred and
line = 1851 | 1 | sixty-nine, and yet that poor Lucy, with four men's blood in her poor
line = 1852 | 1 | veins, could not live even one day? For, had she live one more day, we
line = 1853 | 1 | could have save her. Do you know all the mystery of life and death? Do
line = 1854 | 1 | you know the altogether of comparative anatomy and can say wherefore the
line = 1855 | 1 | qualities of brutes are in some men, and not in others? Can you tell me
line = 1856 | 1 | why, when other spiders die small and soon, that one great spider lived
line = 1857 | 1 | for centuries in the tower of the old Spanish church and grew and grew,
line = 1858 | 1 | till, on descending, he could drink the oil of all the church lamps? Can
line = 1859 | 1 | you tell me why in the Pampas, ay and elsewhere, there are bats that
line = 1860 | 1 | come at night and open the veins of cattle and horses and suck dry their
line = 1861 | 1 | veins; how in some islands of the Western seas there are bats which hang
line = 1862 | 1 | on the trees all day, and those who have seen describe as like giant
line = 1863 | 1 | nuts or pods, and that when the sailors sleep on the deck, because that
line = 1864 | 1 | it is hot, flit down on them, and then--and then in the morning are
line = 1865 | 1 | found dead men, white as even Miss Lucy was?"
line = 1866 | 1 | 
line = 1867 | 1 | "Good God, Professor!" I said, starting up. "Do you mean to tell me that
line = 1868 | 1 | Lucy was bitten by such a bat; and that such a thing is here in London
line = 1869 | 1 | in the nineteenth century?" He waved his hand for silence, and went
line = 1870 | 1 | on:--
line = 1871 | 1 | 
line = 1872 | 1 | "Can you tell me why the tortoise lives more long than generations of
line = 1873 | 1 | men; why the elephant goes on and on till he have seen dynasties; and
line = 1874 | 1 | why the parrot never die only of bite of cat or dog or other complaint?
line = 1875 | 1 | Can you tell me why men believe in all ages and places that there are
line = 1876 | 1 | some few who live on always if they be permit; that there are men and
line = 1877 | 1 | women who cannot die? We all know--because science has vouched for the
line = 1878 | 1 | fact--that there have been toads shut up in rocks for thousands of
line = 1879 | 1 | years, shut in one so small hole that only hold him since the youth of
line = 1880 | 1 | the world. Can you tell me how the Indian fakir can make himself to die
line = 1881 | 1 | and have been buried, and his grave sealed and corn sowed on it, and the
line = 1882 | 1 | corn reaped and be cut and sown and reaped and cut again, and then men
line = 1883 | 1 | come and take away the unbroken seal and that there lie the Indian
line = 1884 | 1 | fakir, not dead, but that rise up and walk amongst them as before?" Here
line = 1885 | 1 | I interrupted him. I was getting bewildered; he so crowded on my mind
line = 1886 | 1 | his list of nature's eccentricities and possible impossibilities that my
line = 1887 | 1 | imagination was getting fired. I had a dim idea that he was teaching me
line = 1888 | 1 | some lesson, as long ago he used to do in his study at Amsterdam; but
line = 1889 | 1 | he used then to tell me the thing, so that I could have the object of
line = 1890 | 1 | thought in mind all the time. But now I was without this help, yet I
line = 1891 | 1 | wanted to follow him, so I said:--
line = 1892 | 1 | 
line = 1893 | 1 | "Professor, let me be your pet student again. Tell me the thesis, so
line = 1894 | 1 | that I may apply your knowledge as you go on. At present I am going in
line = 1895 | 1 | my mind from point to point as a mad man, and not a sane one, follows an
line = 1896 | 1 | idea. I feel like a novice lumbering through a bog in a mist, jumping
line = 1897 | 1 | from one tussock to another in the mere blind effort to move on without
line = 1898 | 1 | knowing where I am going."
line = 1899 | 1 | 
line = 1900 | 1 | "That is good image," he said. "Well, I shall tell you. My thesis is
line = 1901 | 1 | this: I want you to believe."
line = 1902 | 1 | 
line = 1903 | 1 | "To believe what?"
line = 1904 | 1 | 
line = 1905 | 1 | "To believe in things that you cannot. Let me illustrate. I heard once
line = 1906 | 1 | of an American who so defined faith: 'that faculty which enables us to
line = 1907 | 1 | believe things which we know to be untrue.' For one, I follow that man.
line = 1908 | 1 | He meant that we shall have an open mind, and not let a little bit of
line = 1909 | 1 | truth check the rush of a big truth, like a small rock does a railway
line = 1910 | 1 | truck. We get the small truth first. Good! We keep him, and we value
line = 1911 | 1 | him; but all the same we must not let him think himself all the truth in
line = 1912 | 1 | the universe."
line = 1913 | 1 | 
line = 1914 | 1 | "Then you want me not to let some previous conviction injure the
line = 1915 | 1 | receptivity of my mind with regard to some strange matter. Do I read
line = 1916 | 1 | your lesson aright?"
line = 1917 | 1 | 
line = 1918 | 1 | "Ah, you are my favourite pupil still. It is worth to teach you. Now
line = 1919 | 1 | that you are willing to understand, you have taken the first step to
line = 1920 | 1 | understand. You think then that those so small holes in the children's
line = 1921 | 1 | throats were made by the same that made the hole in Miss Lucy?"
line = 1922 | 1 | 
line = 1923 | 1 | "I suppose so." He stood up and said solemnly:--
line = 1924 | 1 | 
line = 1925 | 1 | "Then you are wrong. Oh, would it were so! but alas! no. It is worse,
