line = 2183 | 1 | _27 September._--It was two o'clock before we found a suitable
line = 2184 | 1 | opportunity for our attempt. The funeral held at noon was all completed,
line = 2185 | 1 | and the last stragglers of the mourners had taken themselves lazily
line = 2186 | 1 | away, when, looking carefully from behind a clump of alder-trees, we saw
line = 2187 | 1 | the sexton lock the gate after him. We knew then that we were safe till
line = 2188 | 1 | morning did we desire it; but the Professor told me that we should not
line = 2189 | 1 | want more than an hour at most. Again I felt that horrid sense of the
line = 2190 | 1 | reality of things, in which any effort of imagination seemed out of
line = 2191 | 1 | place; and I realised distinctly the perils of the law which we were
line = 2192 | 1 | incurring in our unhallowed work. Besides, I felt it was all so useless.
line = 2193 | 1 | Outrageous as it was to open a leaden coffin, to see if a woman dead
line = 2194 | 1 | nearly a week were really dead, it now seemed the height of folly to
line = 2195 | 1 | open the tomb again, when we knew, from the evidence of our own
line = 2196 | 1 | eyesight, that the coffin was empty. I shrugged my shoulders, however,
line = 2197 | 1 | and rested silent, for Van Helsing had a way of going on his own road,
line = 2198 | 1 | no matter who remonstrated. He took the key, opened the vault, and again
line = 2199 | 1 | courteously motioned me to precede. The place was not so gruesome as
line = 2200 | 1 | last night, but oh, how unutterably mean-looking when the sunshine
line = 2201 | 1 | streamed in. Van Helsing walked over to Lucy's coffin, and I followed.
line = 2202 | 1 | He bent over and again forced back the leaden flange; and then a shock
line = 2203 | 1 | of surprise and dismay shot through me.
line = 2204 | 1 | 
line = 2205 | 1 | There lay Lucy, seemingly just as we had seen her the night before her
line = 2206 | 1 | funeral. She was, if possible, more radiantly beautiful than ever; and I
line = 2207 | 1 | could not believe that she was dead. The lips were red, nay redder than
line = 2208 | 1 | before; and on the cheeks was a delicate bloom.
line = 2209 | 1 | 
line = 2210 | 1 | "Is this a juggle?" I said to him.
line = 2211 | 1 | 
line = 2212 | 1 | "Are you convinced now?" said the Professor in response, and as he spoke
line = 2213 | 1 | he put over his hand, and in a way that made me shudder, pulled back the
line = 2214 | 1 | dead lips and showed the white teeth.
line = 2215 | 1 | 
line = 2216 | 1 | "See," he went on, "see, they are even sharper than before. With this
line = 2217 | 1 | and this"--and he touched one of the canine teeth and that below
line = 2218 | 1 | it--"the little children can be bitten. Are you of belief now, friend
line = 2219 | 1 | John?" Once more, argumentative hostility woke within me. I _could_ not
line = 2220 | 1 | accept such an overwhelming idea as he suggested; so, with an attempt to
line = 2221 | 1 | argue of which I was even at the moment ashamed, I said:--
line = 2222 | 1 | 
line = 2223 | 1 | "She may have been placed here since last night."
line = 2224 | 1 | 
line = 2225 | 1 | "Indeed? That is so, and by whom?"
line = 2226 | 1 | 
line = 2227 | 1 | "I do not know. Some one has done it."
line = 2228 | 1 | 
line = 2229 | 1 | "And yet she has been dead one week. Most peoples in that time would not
line = 2230 | 1 | look so." I had no answer for this, so was silent. Van Helsing did not
line = 2231 | 1 | seem to notice my silence; at any rate, he showed neither chagrin nor
line = 2232 | 1 | triumph. He was looking intently at the face of the dead woman, raising
line = 2233 | 1 | the eyelids and looking at the eyes, and once more opening the lips and
line = 2234 | 1 | examining the teeth. Then he turned to me and said:--
line = 2235 | 1 | 
line = 2236 | 1 | "Here, there is one thing which is different from all recorded; here is
line = 2237 | 1 | some dual life that is not as the common. She was bitten by the vampire
line = 2238 | 1 | when she was in a trance, sleep-walking--oh, you start; you do not know
line = 2239 | 1 | that, friend John, but you shall know it all later--and in trance could
line = 2240 | 1 | he best come to take more blood. In trance she died, and in trance she
line = 2241 | 1 | is Un-Dead, too. So it is that she differ from all other. Usually when
line = 2242 | 1 | the Un-Dead sleep at home"--as he spoke he made a comprehensive sweep of
line = 2243 | 1 | his arm to designate what to a vampire was "home"--"their face show what
line = 2244 | 1 | they are, but this so sweet that was when she not Un-Dead she go back to
line = 2245 | 1 | the nothings of the common dead. There is no malign there, see, and so
line = 2246 | 1 | it make hard that I must kill her in her sleep." This turned my blood
line = 2247 | 1 | cold, and it began to dawn upon me that I was accepting Van Helsing's
line = 2248 | 1 | theories; but if she were really dead, what was there of terror in the
line = 2249 | 1 | idea of killing her? He looked up at me, and evidently saw the change in
line = 2250 | 1 | my face, for he said almost joyously:--
line = 2251 | 1 | 
line = 2252 | 1 | "Ah, you believe now?"
line = 2253 | 1 | 
line = 2254 | 1 | I answered: "Do not press me too hard all at once. I am willing to
line = 2255 | 1 | accept. How will you do this bloody work?"
line = 2256 | 1 | 
line = 2257 | 1 | "I shall cut off her head and fill her mouth with garlic, and I shall
line = 2258 | 1 | drive a stake through her body." It made me shudder to think of so
line = 2259 | 1 | mutilating the body of the woman whom I had loved. And yet the feeling
line = 2260 | 1 | was not so strong as I had expected. I was, in fact, beginning to
line = 2261 | 1 | shudder at the presence of this being, this Un-Dead, as Van Helsing
line = 2262 | 1 | called it, and to loathe it. Is it possible that love is all subjective,
line = 2263 | 1 | or all objective?
line = 2264 | 1 | 
line = 2265 | 1 | I waited a considerable time for Van Helsing to begin, but he stood as
line = 2266 | 1 | if wrapped in thought. Presently he closed the catch of his bag with a
line = 2267 | 1 | snap, and said:--
line = 2268 | 1 | 
line = 2269 | 1 | "I have been thinking, and have made up my mind as to what is best. If I
line = 2270 | 1 | did simply follow my inclining I would do now, at this moment, what is
line = 2271 | 1 | to be done; but there are other things to follow, and things that are
line = 2272 | 1 | thousand times more difficult in that them we do not know. This is
line = 2273 | 1 | simple. She have yet no life taken, though that is of time; and to act
line = 2274 | 1 | now would be to take danger from her for ever. But then we may have to
line = 2275 | 1 | want Arthur, and how shall we tell him of this? If you, who saw the
line = 2276 | 1 | wounds on Lucy's throat, and saw the wounds so similar on the child's at
line = 2277 | 1 | the hospital; if you, who saw the coffin empty last night and full
line = 2278 | 1 | to-day with a woman who have not change only to be more rose and more
line = 2279 | 1 | beautiful in a whole week, after she die--if you know of this and know
line = 2280 | 1 | of the white figure last night that brought the child to the churchyard,
line = 2281 | 1 | and yet of your own senses you did not believe, how, then, can I expect
line = 2282 | 1 | Arthur, who know none of those things, to believe? He doubted me when I
line = 2283 | 1 | took him from her kiss when she was dying. I know he has forgiven me
line = 2284 | 1 | because in some mistaken idea I have done things that prevent him say
line = 2285 | 1 | good-bye as he ought; and he may think that in some more mistaken idea
line = 2286 | 1 | this woman was buried alive; and that in most mistake of all we have
line = 2287 | 1 | killed her. He will then argue back that it is we, mistaken ones, that
line = 2288 | 1 | have killed her by our ideas; and so he will be much unhappy always. Yet
line = 2289 | 1 | he never can be sure; and that is the worst of all. And he will
line = 2290 | 1 | sometimes think that she he loved was buried alive, and that will paint
line = 2291 | 1 | his dreams with horrors of what she must have suffered; and again, he
line = 2292 | 1 | will think that we may be right, and that his so beloved was, after all,
line = 2293 | 1 | an Un-Dead. No! I told him once, and since then I learn much. Now, since
line = 2294 | 1 | I know it is all true, a hundred thousand times more do I know that he
line = 2295 | 1 | must pass through the bitter waters to reach the sweet. He, poor fellow,
line = 2296 | 1 | must have one hour that will make the very face of heaven grow black to
line = 2297 | 1 | him; then we can act for good all round and send him peace. My mind is
line = 2298 | 1 | made up. Let us go. You return home for to-night to your asylum, and see
line = 2299 | 1 | that all be well. As for me, I shall spend the night here in this
line = 2300 | 1 | churchyard in my own way. To-morrow night you will come to me to the
line = 2301 | 1 | Berkeley Hotel at ten of the clock. I shall send for Arthur to come too,
line = 2302 | 1 | and also that so fine young man of America that gave his blood. Later we
line = 2303 | 1 | shall all have work to do. I come with you so far as Piccadilly and
line = 2304 | 1 | there dine, for I must be back here before the sun set."
line = 2305 | 1 | 
line = 2306 | 1 | So we locked the tomb and came away, and got over the wall of the
line = 2307 | 1 | churchyard, which was not much of a task, and drove back to Piccadilly.
