line = 2315 | 1 | "_27 September._
line = 2316 | 1 | 
line = 2317 | 1 | "Friend John,--
line = 2318 | 1 | 
line = 2319 | 1 | "I write this in case anything should happen. I go alone to watch in
line = 2320 | 1 | that churchyard. It pleases me that the Un-Dead, Miss Lucy, shall not
line = 2321 | 1 | leave to-night, that so on the morrow night she may be more eager.
line = 2322 | 1 | Therefore I shall fix some things she like not--garlic and a
line = 2323 | 1 | crucifix--and so seal up the door of the tomb. She is young as Un-Dead,
line = 2324 | 1 | and will heed. Moreover, these are only to prevent her coming out; they
line = 2325 | 1 | may not prevail on her wanting to get in; for then the Un-Dead is
line = 2326 | 1 | desperate, and must find the line of least resistance, whatsoever it may
line = 2327 | 1 | be. I shall be at hand all the night from sunset till after the sunrise,
line = 2328 | 1 | and if there be aught that may be learned I shall learn it. For Miss
line = 2329 | 1 | Lucy or from her, I have no fear; but that other to whom is there that
line = 2330 | 1 | she is Un-Dead, he have now the power to seek her tomb and find shelter.
line = 2331 | 1 | He is cunning, as I know from Mr. Jonathan and from the way that all
line = 2332 | 1 | along he have fooled us when he played with us for Miss Lucy's life, and
line = 2333 | 1 | we lost; and in many ways the Un-Dead are strong. He have always the
line = 2334 | 1 | strength in his hand of twenty men; even we four who gave our strength
line = 2335 | 1 | to Miss Lucy it also is all to him. Besides, he can summon his wolf and
line = 2336 | 1 | I know not what. So if it be that he come thither on this night he shall
line = 2337 | 1 | find me; but none other shall--until it be too late. But it may be that
line = 2338 | 1 | he will not attempt the place. There is no reason why he should; his
line = 2339 | 1 | hunting ground is more full of game than the churchyard where the
line = 2340 | 1 | Un-Dead woman sleep, and the one old man watch.
line = 2341 | 1 | 
line = 2342 | 1 | "Therefore I write this in case.... Take the papers that are with this,
line = 2343 | 1 | the diaries of Harker and the rest, and read them, and then find this
line = 2344 | 1 | great Un-Dead, and cut off his head and burn his heart or drive a stake
line = 2345 | 1 | through it, so that the world may rest from him.
line = 2346 | 1 | 
line = 2347 | 1 | "If it be so, farewell.
line = 2348 | 1 | 
line = 2349 | 1 | "VAN HELSING."
line = 2350 | 1 | 
line = 2351 | 1 | 
line = 2352 | 1 | 
line = 2353 | 1 | _Dr. Seward's Diary._
line = 2354 | 1 | 
line = 2355 | 1 | _28 September._--It is wonderful what a good night's sleep will do for
line = 2356 | 1 | one. Yesterday I was almost willing to accept Van Helsing's monstrous
line = 2357 | 1 | ideas; but now they seem to start out lurid before me as outrages on
line = 2358 | 1 | common sense. I have no doubt that he believes it all. I wonder if his
line = 2359 | 1 | mind can have become in any way unhinged. Surely there must be _some_
line = 2360 | 1 | rational explanation of all these mysterious things. Is it possible that
line = 2361 | 1 | the Professor can have done it himself? He is so abnormally clever that
line = 2362 | 1 | if he went off his head he would carry out his intent with regard to
line = 2363 | 1 | some fixed idea in a wonderful way. I am loath to think it, and indeed
line = 2364 | 1 | it would be almost as great a marvel as the other to find that Van
line = 2365 | 1 | Helsing was mad; but anyhow I shall watch him carefully. I may get some
line = 2366 | 1 | light on the mystery.
line = 2367 | 1 | 
line = 2368 | 1 |        *       *       *       *       *
line = 2369 | 1 | 
line = 2370 | 1 | _29 September, morning._.... Last night, at a little before ten o'clock,
line = 2371 | 1 | Arthur and Quincey came into Van Helsing's room; he told us all that he
line = 2372 | 1 | wanted us to do, but especially addressing himself to Arthur, as if all
line = 2373 | 1 | our wills were centred in his. He began by saying that he hoped we would
line = 2374 | 1 | all come with him too, "for," he said, "there is a grave duty to be done
line = 2375 | 1 | there. You were doubtless surprised at my letter?" This query was
line = 2376 | 1 | directly addressed to Lord Godalming.
line = 2377 | 1 | 
line = 2378 | 1 | "I was. It rather upset me for a bit. There has been so much trouble
line = 2379 | 1 | around my house of late that I could do without any more. I have been
line = 2380 | 1 | curious, too, as to what you mean. Quincey and I talked it over; but the
line = 2381 | 1 | more we talked, the more puzzled we got, till now I can say for myself
line = 2382 | 1 | that I'm about up a tree as to any meaning about anything."
line = 2383 | 1 | 
line = 2384 | 1 | "Me too," said Quincey Morris laconically.
line = 2385 | 1 | 
line = 2386 | 1 | "Oh," said the Professor, "then you are nearer the beginning, both of
line = 2387 | 1 | you, than friend John here, who has to go a long way back before he can
