line = 2389 | 1 | 
line = 2390 | 1 | It was evident that he recognised my return to my old doubting frame of
line = 2391 | 1 | mind without my saying a word. Then, turning to the other two, he said
line = 2392 | 1 | with intense gravity:--
line = 2393 | 1 | 
line = 2394 | 1 | "I want your permission to do what I think good this night. It is, I
line = 2395 | 1 | know, much to ask; and when you know what it is I propose to do you will
line = 2396 | 1 | know, and only then, how much. Therefore may I ask that you promise me
line = 2397 | 1 | in the dark, so that afterwards, though you may be angry with me for a
line = 2398 | 1 | time--I must not disguise from myself the possibility that such may
line = 2399 | 1 | be--you shall not blame yourselves for anything."
line = 2400 | 1 | 
line = 2401 | 1 | "That's frank anyhow," broke in Quincey. "I'll answer for the Professor.
line = 2402 | 1 | I don't quite see his drift, but I swear he's honest; and that's good
line = 2403 | 1 | enough for me."
line = 2404 | 1 | 
line = 2405 | 1 | "I thank you, sir," said Van Helsing proudly. "I have done myself the
line = 2406 | 1 | honour of counting you one trusting friend, and such endorsement is dear
line = 2407 | 1 | to me." He held out a hand, which Quincey took.
line = 2408 | 1 | 
line = 2409 | 1 | Then Arthur spoke out:--
line = 2410 | 1 | 
line = 2411 | 1 | "Dr. Van Helsing, I don't quite like to 'buy a pig in a poke,' as they
line = 2412 | 1 | say in Scotland, and if it be anything in which my honour as a gentleman
line = 2413 | 1 | or my faith as a Christian is concerned, I cannot make such a promise.
line = 2414 | 1 | If you can assure me that what you intend does not violate either of
line = 2415 | 1 | these two, then I give my consent at once; though for the life of me, I
line = 2416 | 1 | cannot understand what you are driving at."
line = 2417 | 1 | 
line = 2418 | 1 | "I accept your limitation," said Van Helsing, "and all I ask of you is
line = 2419 | 1 | that if you feel it necessary to condemn any act of mine, you will first
line = 2420 | 1 | consider it well and be satisfied that it does not violate your
line = 2421 | 1 | reservations."
line = 2422 | 1 | 
line = 2423 | 1 | "Agreed!" said Arthur; "that is only fair. And now that the
line = 2424 | 1 | _pourparlers_ are over, may I ask what it is we are to do?"
line = 2425 | 1 | 
line = 2426 | 1 | "I want you to come with me, and to come in secret, to the churchyard at
line = 2427 | 1 | Kingstead."
line = 2428 | 1 | 
line = 2429 | 1 | Arthur's face fell as he said in an amazed sort of way:--
line = 2430 | 1 | 
line = 2431 | 1 | "Where poor Lucy is buried?" The Professor bowed. Arthur went on: "And
line = 2432 | 1 | when there?"
line = 2433 | 1 | 
line = 2434 | 1 | "To enter the tomb!" Arthur stood up.
line = 2435 | 1 | 
line = 2436 | 1 | "Professor, are you in earnest; or it is some monstrous joke? Pardon me,
line = 2437 | 1 | I see that you are in earnest." He sat down again, but I could see that
line = 2438 | 1 | he sat firmly and proudly, as one who is on his dignity. There was
line = 2439 | 1 | silence until he asked again:--
line = 2440 | 1 | 
line = 2441 | 1 | "And when in the tomb?"
line = 2442 | 1 | 
line = 2443 | 1 | "To open the coffin."
line = 2444 | 1 | 
line = 2445 | 1 | "This is too much!" he said, angrily rising again. "I am willing to be
line = 2446 | 1 | patient in all things that are reasonable; but in this--this desecration
line = 2447 | 1 | of the grave--of one who----" He fairly choked with indignation. The
line = 2448 | 1 | Professor looked pityingly at him.
line = 2449 | 1 | 
line = 2450 | 1 | "If I could spare you one pang, my poor friend," he said, "God knows I
line = 2451 | 1 | would. But this night our feet must tread in thorny paths; or later, and
line = 2452 | 1 | for ever, the feet you love must walk in paths of flame!"
line = 2453 | 1 | 
line = 2454 | 1 | Arthur looked up with set white face and said:--
line = 2455 | 1 | 
line = 2456 | 1 | "Take care, sir, take care!"
line = 2457 | 1 | 
line = 2458 | 1 | "Would it not be well to hear what I have to say?" said Van Helsing.
line = 2459 | 1 | "And then you will at least know the limit of my purpose. Shall I go
line = 2460 | 1 | on?"
line = 2461 | 1 | 
line = 2462 | 1 | "That's fair enough," broke in Morris.
line = 2463 | 1 | 
line = 2464 | 1 | After a pause Van Helsing went on, evidently with an effort:--
line = 2465 | 1 | 
